1
00:01:45,397 --> 00:01:46,857
What about Asta?

2
00:01:46,940 --> 00:01:49,067
He'll have to go in
the baggage car, won't he?

3
00:01:49,151 --> 00:01:51,278
Why should he have
any special privileges?

4
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:53,405
He'll ride with us
in the day coach and like it.

5
00:01:53,488 --> 00:01:54,906
But those are the rules,
aren't they?

6
00:01:54,990 --> 00:01:58,619
Well... we'll camouflage him
under your coat.

7
00:01:58,702 --> 00:02:00,495
Out of sight, out of mind.
It's a cinch.

8
00:02:00,579 --> 00:02:02,873
Uh, two to Sycamore Springs,
please.

9
00:02:16,637 --> 00:02:18,180
[whining]

10
00:02:20,682 --> 00:02:22,392
Oh! Nick! Asta!
Catch him!

11
00:02:22,476 --> 00:02:23,560
Here.
You get them.

12
00:02:23,644 --> 00:02:25,228
Asta!

13
00:02:27,439 --> 00:02:28,774
Asta?

14
00:02:28,857 --> 00:02:30,025
Asta!

15
00:02:37,783 --> 00:02:38,950
Asta?

16
00:02:40,202 --> 00:02:41,703
Alright, come on.

17
00:02:50,379 --> 00:02:53,090
[growling playfully]

18
00:02:57,719 --> 00:02:59,805
Here, here.
What's going on?

19
00:02:59,888 --> 00:03:01,264
Nick Charles.

20
00:03:01,348 --> 00:03:02,349
Hiya, Clancey.

21
00:03:02,432 --> 00:03:03,600
Nick, I'm surprised
at you.

22
00:03:03,684 --> 00:03:05,352
I thought you could
handle a stout.

23
00:03:05,435 --> 00:03:07,020
I tripped.
I was chasing my dog.

24
00:03:07,104 --> 00:03:09,064
Oh, sure.

25
00:03:09,147 --> 00:03:12,401
Clancey, I've had nothing
but a swig of cider all day.

26
00:03:12,484 --> 00:03:13,819
Nicky, are you hurt?

27
00:03:13,902 --> 00:03:15,654
I think he hurt
his head, Mrs. Charles.

28
00:03:15,737 --> 00:03:16,863
He's been saying
something about

29
00:03:16,947 --> 00:03:17,906
not drinking nothing
but cider.

30
00:03:17,989 --> 00:03:19,157
And it's true.

31
00:03:19,241 --> 00:03:20,409
He's going down
to visit his folks,

32
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:21,993
and they don't like
drinking.

33
00:03:22,077 --> 00:03:24,788
Let's get down to the train
and get comfortable.

34
00:03:24,871 --> 00:03:27,040
Ha! Camouflage,
you know.

35
00:03:27,124 --> 00:03:28,083
Oh, yes.

36
00:03:28,166 --> 00:03:29,418
Thanks, Clancey.

37
00:03:31,545 --> 00:03:33,422
[train whistle blowing]

38
00:03:35,507 --> 00:03:36,967
Pardon me.

39
00:03:41,513 --> 00:03:43,348
It's cozy, isn't it?

40
00:03:43,432 --> 00:03:45,934
C'est la guerre, madam.
C'est la guerre.

41
00:03:46,017 --> 00:03:48,019
That's French
for "bottoms up.”

42
00:03:48,103 --> 00:03:49,396
Tickets, please.

43
00:03:49,479 --> 00:03:52,774
Nicky, you really
like cider?

44
00:03:52,858 --> 00:03:54,359
Like it?
I love it.

45
00:03:54,443 --> 00:03:57,237
Why, just the pure,
natural juice of the apple.

46
00:03:57,320 --> 00:03:58,905
What could be better,
for instance?

47
00:03:58,989 --> 00:04:01,825
A dry martini,
for instance.

48
00:04:01,908 --> 00:04:03,201
That horrible stuff?

49
00:04:03,285 --> 00:04:04,828
Almost took the lining
off my stomach.

50
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:06,788
Why do you care?
It didn't show.

51
00:04:09,040 --> 00:04:11,334
Good gracious!

52
00:04:11,418 --> 00:04:12,711
Nicky!

53
00:04:12,794 --> 00:04:14,004
Blockbuster.

54
00:04:14,087 --> 00:04:15,589
Ooh. Yes.

55
00:04:15,672 --> 00:04:16,798
Uh!

56
00:04:16,882 --> 00:04:18,258
Upsy-daisy.

57
00:04:18,341 --> 00:04:19,509
[clears throat]

58
00:04:19,593 --> 00:04:21,178
Oh!

59
00:04:21,261 --> 00:04:22,596
Tickets, please.

60
00:04:22,679 --> 00:04:23,889
You know, mammy,
I don't think

61
00:04:23,972 --> 00:04:25,432
you're taking
this reform movement

62
00:04:25,515 --> 00:04:26,850
of mine very seriously.

63
00:04:26,933 --> 00:04:28,101
Not very.

64
00:04:28,185 --> 00:04:29,352
Well,
you just wait.

65
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:30,479
A couple of weeks
on this cider,

66
00:04:30,562 --> 00:04:31,772
and i'll be
a new man.

67
00:04:31,855 --> 00:04:33,398
I sort of liked
the old one.

68
00:04:34,274 --> 00:04:35,567
Why, darling,

69
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:36,860
that's the nicest
thing you said to me

70
00:04:36,943 --> 00:04:37,986
since the time
i got my head caught

71
00:04:38,069 --> 00:04:39,529
in that cuspidor
at the Waldorf.

72
00:04:39,613 --> 00:04:42,616
That wasn't the Waldorf.
That was the Astor.

73
00:04:42,699 --> 00:04:44,117
Astor?

74
00:04:44,201 --> 00:04:46,119
Astor.

75
00:04:46,203 --> 00:04:48,497
All animals must go
in the baggage car.

76
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:49,831
Oh, that's
not an animal.

77
00:04:49,915 --> 00:04:51,416
That's
my fur coat.

78
00:04:51,500 --> 00:04:54,127
If it can wag its tail,
it goes in the baggage car.

79
00:04:57,881 --> 00:05:00,258
So, it was going
to be a cinch, eh?

80
00:05:01,510 --> 00:05:03,178
Very well.

81
00:05:03,261 --> 00:05:05,430
Credit me with an error.

82
00:05:09,100 --> 00:05:11,353
Hey. Hey, mister.

83
00:05:11,436 --> 00:05:12,729
When you pass
the kitchen,

84
00:05:12,813 --> 00:05:15,398
will you ask the chef
to warm this up?

85
00:05:16,900 --> 00:05:18,777
I don't
dance, bub.

86
00:05:20,904 --> 00:05:22,489
Body
temperature.

87
00:05:26,368 --> 00:05:29,830
Good grief!
Are you on milk now?

88
00:05:29,913 --> 00:05:31,081
I'm warming this up
for a friend.

89
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:32,332
Oh!

90
00:05:32,415 --> 00:05:34,334
Oh, I beg
your pardon.

91
00:05:34,417 --> 00:05:36,086
Why, if it isn't
Nick Charles.

92
00:05:36,169 --> 00:05:37,379
Where did you
drop in from?

93
00:05:37,462 --> 00:05:38,797
You sure are a sight
for sore eyes.

94
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:40,257
Hiya, Brogan.

95
00:05:40,340 --> 00:05:41,842
Well, cut off my legs
and call me shorty.

96
00:05:41,925 --> 00:05:43,009
It's a small world,
ain't it?

97
00:05:43,093 --> 00:05:44,052
Ain't it?

98
00:05:44,135 --> 00:05:45,303
Where
are you going?

99
00:05:45,387 --> 00:05:46,471
We're off on
a little vacation,

100
00:05:46,555 --> 00:05:47,722
Sycamore Springs.

101
00:05:47,806 --> 00:05:50,392
I getit. I get it.
I'll play dummy.

102
00:05:50,475 --> 00:05:52,435
Oh, you're on
the wrong horse, Brogan.

103
00:05:52,519 --> 00:05:53,770
This is Mrs. Charles.

104
00:05:53,854 --> 00:05:55,480
Oh, sure, sure.

105
00:05:55,564 --> 00:05:57,941
[sarcastically]
How do you do, Mrs. Charles?

106
00:05:58,024 --> 00:05:59,651
So, uh, what are
you doing these days?

107
00:05:59,734 --> 00:06:00,694
Traveling
in postcards.

108
00:06:00,777 --> 00:06:02,153
Pardon?

109
00:06:02,237 --> 00:06:04,155
Postcards. Postcards.
Seasonal greetings.

110
00:06:04,239 --> 00:06:06,741
Say, I cover
Sycamore Springs.

111
00:06:06,825 --> 00:06:08,076
I'll look you up
on the way back.

112
00:06:08,159 --> 00:06:09,911
That will be nice.

113
00:06:09,995 --> 00:06:11,121
Well, so long.

114
00:06:11,204 --> 00:06:12,873
So long.

115
00:06:12,956 --> 00:06:14,165
Nick,
how am i doing?

116
00:06:14,249 --> 00:06:15,542
Oh, swell.

117
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:16,877
Stick close to me
in Sycamore Springs.

118
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:19,421
Right. How's
my postcard chatter?

119
00:06:19,504 --> 00:06:20,797
Alright,
but look,

120
00:06:20,881 --> 00:06:21,840
don't those
greeting cards

121
00:06:21,923 --> 00:06:23,800
have some poems
or mottos?

122
00:06:23,884 --> 00:06:24,885
I think so.

123
00:06:24,968 --> 00:06:26,303
Yeah. Well,
memorize a few.

124
00:06:26,386 --> 00:06:27,429
You mean like,

125
00:06:27,512 --> 00:06:28,889
"Roses are red
violets are blue

126
00:06:28,972 --> 00:06:30,515
a happy birthday is
what i'm wishing you?"

127
00:06:30,599 --> 00:06:32,142
Yes, that's it...
roughly.

128
00:06:33,435 --> 00:06:34,603
I get it.

129
00:06:34,686 --> 00:06:36,438
[train whistle blowing]

130
00:06:36,521 --> 00:06:39,149
"Willa Wanna,
Desdemona,

131
00:06:39,232 --> 00:06:40,775
"Minnetonka,
Nippewana."

132
00:06:40,859 --> 00:06:43,028
How far is that
baggage car, anyway?

133
00:06:43,111 --> 00:06:44,362
<i>Oh, imagine
it's somewhere</i>

134
00:06:44,446 --> 00:06:46,615
between Pocahontas
and Sitting Bull.

135
00:06:48,992 --> 00:06:50,035
Well.

136
00:06:52,537 --> 00:06:54,539
Any suggestions?

137
00:06:54,623 --> 00:06:55,790
Make like
an eel, mama.

138
00:06:55,874 --> 00:06:57,834
[train whistle blowing]

139
00:06:57,918 --> 00:06:59,544
Woman: More people.

140
00:06:59,628 --> 00:07:01,463
[people groaning]

141
00:07:01,546 --> 00:07:03,131
Oh, I'm sorry.

142
00:07:05,717 --> 00:07:07,594
Oh, my cigar.

143
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:09,387
And that was my
last one, too.

144
00:07:09,471 --> 00:07:11,264
Excuse me.

145
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:12,891
Would you please
let me pass?

146
00:07:12,974 --> 00:07:14,225
Why should i?

147
00:07:14,309 --> 00:07:16,019
Oh!

148
00:07:16,102 --> 00:07:17,479
Well!

149
00:07:17,562 --> 00:07:19,522
How'd you like to be
married to that type?

150
00:07:24,694 --> 00:07:26,488
Oh, excuse me.

151
00:07:26,571 --> 00:07:27,656
Oh, my word.

152
00:07:27,739 --> 00:07:29,908
I'm so sorry.

153
00:07:29,991 --> 00:07:32,410
Why don't you look
where you're going?

154
00:07:34,746 --> 00:07:36,539
Darling,
are you sure

155
00:07:36,623 --> 00:07:38,375
you're rubbing these people
the right way?

156
00:07:40,627 --> 00:07:41,878
Uh-oh.

157
00:07:44,756 --> 00:07:46,383
The blockbuster.

158
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:49,302
Woman: Isn't
that terrible?

159
00:07:49,386 --> 00:07:52,514
Ow! My foot!

160
00:07:52,597 --> 00:07:55,809
My foot!

161
00:07:55,892 --> 00:07:57,686
Will you please
let us through?

162
00:07:57,769 --> 00:07:59,104
Well!

163
00:08:00,647 --> 00:08:03,149
Oh, certainly.

164
00:08:03,233 --> 00:08:05,318
Make way for this lady
and her baby.

165
00:08:05,402 --> 00:08:08,154
Make way. She wants to get
to the dining car.

166
00:08:08,238 --> 00:08:10,865
Make way for the mother.
Follow me.

167
00:08:10,949 --> 00:08:12,158
[train whistle blowing]

168
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:13,451
[goats bleating]

169
00:08:16,454 --> 00:08:17,622
[Asta barking]

170
00:08:20,125 --> 00:08:23,044
[ducks quacking]

171
00:08:23,962 --> 00:08:25,463
[barking]

172
00:08:25,547 --> 00:08:26,881
[quack]

173
00:08:26,965 --> 00:08:28,466
[whimpering]

174
00:08:28,550 --> 00:08:31,094
Ha ha!
Bad strategy, Asta.

175
00:08:31,177 --> 00:08:33,513
You forgot to protect
your rear flank.

176
00:08:33,596 --> 00:08:34,556
Nicky?

177
00:08:34,639 --> 00:08:35,640
Hmm?

178
00:08:35,724 --> 00:08:36,891
I still
don't understand

179
00:08:36,975 --> 00:08:38,560
what gave you
this sudden desire

180
00:08:38,643 --> 00:08:41,396
to go back to Sycamore Springs
after all these years.

181
00:08:41,479 --> 00:08:44,065
Well, it'll make
a nice vacation, won't it?

182
00:08:44,149 --> 00:08:46,151
A chance to see
mother and dad.

183
00:08:46,234 --> 00:08:47,819
I'll bet they're
anxious to see you,

184
00:08:47,902 --> 00:08:49,112
and not just
the family.

185
00:08:49,195 --> 00:08:50,697
The whole town
will probably turn out.

186
00:08:50,780 --> 00:08:52,907
After all, you are
the local boy who made good.

187
00:08:52,991 --> 00:08:55,493
Oh, now, darling,
come, come.

188
00:08:55,577 --> 00:08:57,120
Oh, don't be
so modest, Nicky.

189
00:08:57,203 --> 00:08:58,455
Won't it feel
good to get

190
00:08:58,538 --> 00:09:00,540
a pat on the back
from your old man?

191
00:09:00,623 --> 00:09:02,333
A pat on the back?
What would i do with it?

192
00:09:02,417 --> 00:09:04,127
Ah, don't kid me.
If your father

193
00:09:04,210 --> 00:09:05,712
ever gave you
a pat on the back,

194
00:09:05,795 --> 00:09:08,214
you'd pop your vest buttons
all over the parlor rug.

195
00:09:08,298 --> 00:09:10,425
You just don't know
my vest buttons.

196
00:09:10,508 --> 00:09:11,801
Look!

197
00:09:11,885 --> 00:09:14,929
Darling, see it?
The old windmill.

198
00:09:16,514 --> 00:09:18,349
It's still there.

199
00:09:18,433 --> 00:09:19,434
You know, when i
was a little punk,

200
00:09:19,517 --> 00:09:21,102
that was
my secret hideaway.

201
00:09:21,186 --> 00:09:22,604
Good heavens.
What secrets

202
00:09:22,687 --> 00:09:24,314
were you hiding
in those days?

203
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:27,275
Oh, corn silk,
detective stories.

204
00:09:27,358 --> 00:09:30,236
And look, right there was
the little old schoolhouse.

205
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:32,655
Ha ha. You know,
once on Halloween,

206
00:09:32,739 --> 00:09:34,365
I burned it down...
slightly.

207
00:09:34,449 --> 00:09:36,618
That must have handed
your father a big laugh.

208
00:09:36,701 --> 00:09:38,244
Yes. He just roared...

209
00:09:38,328 --> 00:09:40,580
all the way
to the woodshed with me.

210
00:09:40,663 --> 00:09:43,124
Nicky, you never
got along,

211
00:09:43,208 --> 00:09:45,418
you and your father,
did you?

212
00:09:45,502 --> 00:09:47,003
Never got along?

213
00:09:47,087 --> 00:09:48,755
I wonder what ever
gave you that impression.

214
00:09:48,838 --> 00:09:51,966
Oh, he's never come
to see us in New York.

215
00:09:52,050 --> 00:09:55,011
Well, he's pretty
busy, you know.

216
00:09:55,095 --> 00:09:56,888
Of course, there is
one other little thing.

217
00:09:56,971 --> 00:09:59,516
He, uh... he thinks
i play too hard.

218
00:09:59,599 --> 00:10:01,017
Indeed?

219
00:10:01,101 --> 00:10:03,353
And drink too hard.

220
00:10:03,436 --> 00:10:04,854
Wonder what ever gave him
that impression.

221
00:10:04,938 --> 00:10:06,481
[train whistle blows]

222
00:10:06,564 --> 00:10:08,525
Sycamore Springs.
This is you, folks.

223
00:10:08,608 --> 00:10:12,195
Well, we're very much
obliged to you.

224
00:10:12,278 --> 00:10:13,488
Buy yourself
a little smoke.

225
00:10:13,571 --> 00:10:15,156
Thanks, but...

226
00:10:15,240 --> 00:10:16,533
Compliments
of the pup.

227
00:10:16,616 --> 00:10:17,826
Spitz?

228
00:10:17,909 --> 00:10:19,577
No, just growls.

229
00:10:24,958 --> 00:10:26,668
[goat bleats]

230
00:10:33,049 --> 00:10:37,220
Ha ha. That's funny.

231
00:10:37,303 --> 00:10:38,304
I wonder if they
got my letter.

232
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:39,556
Of course they did.

233
00:10:39,639 --> 00:10:41,891
There's your
reception committee.

234
00:10:41,975 --> 00:10:44,018
Oh.
It's Crazy Mary.

235
00:10:44,102 --> 00:10:45,728
She's a town
character.

236
00:10:47,814 --> 00:10:49,524
Hello, Mary.
Remember me?

237
00:10:49,607 --> 00:10:51,067
Yeah.
Nick Charles.

238
00:10:51,151 --> 00:10:53,153
Yes, that's right.
Darling, this is Mary.

239
00:10:53,236 --> 00:10:54,737
- Hello, Mary.
- My wife.

240
00:10:54,821 --> 00:10:56,531
Poor woman.
Where's the baby?

241
00:10:56,614 --> 00:10:58,241
I heard
you had a baby.

242
00:10:58,324 --> 00:11:01,661
Baby. Oh...
baby. Baby.

243
00:11:03,872 --> 00:11:05,832
What's he
going to do now?

244
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:07,125
I don't know.

245
00:11:09,419 --> 00:11:10,545
Desdemona!

246
00:11:12,755 --> 00:11:14,716
That's crazy Nick.

247
00:11:14,799 --> 00:11:16,634
He was always
like that.

248
00:11:23,683 --> 00:11:24,809
[growling]

249
00:11:26,269 --> 00:11:28,396
[barking]

250
00:11:30,023 --> 00:11:31,691
Asta, no.

251
00:11:34,027 --> 00:11:35,987
Let's surprise them,
huh, sweet?

252
00:11:55,131 --> 00:11:56,257
- Uh!
- Shh.

253
00:11:57,550 --> 00:11:58,551
It's a surprise.

254
00:11:58,635 --> 00:11:59,844
The doctor
isn't in.

255
00:11:59,928 --> 00:12:01,095
No?

256
00:12:01,179 --> 00:12:02,597
But you can go to
Dr. Clayworth.

257
00:12:02,680 --> 00:12:04,265
He's just down
the street.

258
00:12:04,349 --> 00:12:05,767
Is Mrs. Charles in?

259
00:12:05,850 --> 00:12:07,435
She's
in the kitchen.

260
00:12:08,811 --> 00:12:10,188
Shh.

261
00:12:12,565 --> 00:12:13,983
Shh.

262
00:12:20,156 --> 00:12:21,282
What's
cooking, ma?

263
00:12:21,366 --> 00:12:23,451
Oh, just making
a little tea.

264
00:12:25,036 --> 00:12:27,789
Nick! Nick,
my darling!

265
00:12:27,872 --> 00:12:28,831
Oh!

266
00:12:28,915 --> 00:12:29,999
Hiya, ma.

267
00:12:30,083 --> 00:12:31,125
How wonderful
that you could

268
00:12:31,209 --> 00:12:32,502
get here for
your birthday.

269
00:12:32,585 --> 00:12:33,544
Wasn't it?

270
00:12:33,628 --> 00:12:34,796
Nora!

271
00:12:34,879 --> 00:12:36,089
Hello, dear.

272
00:12:36,172 --> 00:12:38,216
What a lovely suit.

273
00:12:38,299 --> 00:12:39,676
Why didn't you tell me
you were coming?

274
00:12:39,759 --> 00:12:41,135
Didn't dad
get my letter?

275
00:12:41,219 --> 00:12:43,513
Why, no. He didn't say
anything to me about it.

276
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:46,224
Wait a moment.
That's what he must have meant

277
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:48,476
when he said there would be
two extra for dinner.

278
00:12:48,559 --> 00:12:51,312
Oh, your father.
Where's junior?

279
00:12:51,396 --> 00:12:52,855
Oh, we didn't want to
take him out of school.

280
00:12:52,939 --> 00:12:54,691
He's going to kindergarten
now and loves it.

281
00:12:54,774 --> 00:12:56,901
Oh, he must be
simply huge by now.

282
00:12:56,985 --> 00:12:58,820
Hello, Asta.
Oh, I'm so excited.

283
00:12:58,903 --> 00:13:00,947
Come along.
I'll get you two settled.

284
00:13:01,030 --> 00:13:02,282
You know something?

285
00:13:02,365 --> 00:13:03,950
I believe the plan
is going through.

286
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:05,034
For the hospital?

287
00:13:05,118 --> 00:13:06,411
Yes. Isn't it
wonderful?

288
00:13:06,494 --> 00:13:07,787
You know, Nora,
they're going to build

289
00:13:07,870 --> 00:13:09,205
a hospital
for the doctor

290
00:13:09,289 --> 00:13:10,623
with a laboratory
for his research work.

291
00:13:10,707 --> 00:13:12,875
It's something he's
dreamed of all his life.

292
00:13:12,959 --> 00:13:15,336
Why, good heavens, Hilda.
What are you doing there?

293
00:13:15,420 --> 00:13:18,298
Take the bags
upstairs.

294
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:19,632
Are you alright?

295
00:13:19,716 --> 00:13:21,634
Why, of course
i'm alright.

296
00:13:21,718 --> 00:13:23,720
This is my son,
the famous detective.

297
00:13:25,722 --> 00:13:27,140
Oh!

298
00:13:27,223 --> 00:13:29,976
What is the matter
with you, Hilda?

299
00:13:30,059 --> 00:13:31,602
Detective?

300
00:13:33,646 --> 00:13:34,814
Now, this is
all your fault.

301
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:36,024
Mine?

302
00:13:36,107 --> 00:13:37,317
Yes. It only behaves
like this

303
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:38,359
when there's excitement
in the house.

304
00:13:38,443 --> 00:13:39,652
Do you mean
to tell me

305
00:13:39,736 --> 00:13:41,029
that this table
hasn't been fixed yet?

306
00:13:41,112 --> 00:13:42,155
Well, if you want
to make yourself useful,

307
00:13:42,238 --> 00:13:43,448
you can fix it.

308
00:13:43,531 --> 00:13:44,574
There's a screwdriver
in the kitchen.

309
00:13:44,657 --> 00:13:45,992
I don't need
a screwdriver.

310
00:13:46,075 --> 00:13:47,660
I've got a little gadget
right here in my pocket

311
00:13:47,744 --> 00:13:49,370
that will do anything,
from manicuring to safecracking.

312
00:13:49,454 --> 00:13:51,039
Safecracking.
Nicky.

313
00:13:51,122 --> 00:13:52,957
Now, how did this
get in here?

314
00:13:53,041 --> 00:13:54,959
Come along. Come along
and help me with the tea.

315
00:13:55,043 --> 00:13:56,753
And take off your pretty hat.

316
00:14:07,597 --> 00:14:08,765
Oh.

317
00:14:11,434 --> 00:14:12,602
[clang]

318
00:14:16,981 --> 00:14:20,109
Just a little
elbow grease.

319
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:21,527
[growling playfully]

320
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:22,820
Here we are.

321
00:14:27,617 --> 00:14:30,745
Now, that's the last time
that'll ever come down.

322
00:14:32,997 --> 00:14:34,540
[whimpering]

323
00:14:37,293 --> 00:14:38,461
Uh-oh.

324
00:14:42,048 --> 00:14:43,174
Nora: Oh, doctor.

325
00:14:43,257 --> 00:14:45,259
Oh, Nora, dear.
I'm so sorry

326
00:14:45,343 --> 00:14:46,803
i missed you
at the station.

327
00:14:46,886 --> 00:14:49,347
Oh, that's alright.
I managed to get him here.

328
00:14:49,430 --> 00:14:51,724
Yes,
so i see.

329
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:52,767
Hiya, pop.

330
00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:54,310
Hello, son.
Well...

331
00:14:54,394 --> 00:14:55,895
let's get him
on his feet.

332
00:14:57,480 --> 00:14:58,815
Come on.
Up you come.

333
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:01,234
You know, I was just
fixing this table...

334
00:15:01,317 --> 00:15:02,610
Yes, I know,

335
00:15:02,693 --> 00:15:04,862
and i suppose that's
furniture polish??

336
00:15:04,946 --> 00:15:06,322
That, dad, is cider.

337
00:15:06,406 --> 00:15:08,032
- Uh-huh.
- Taste it.

338
00:15:08,116 --> 00:15:09,200
Oh, I don't have to.
I believe you.

339
00:15:09,283 --> 00:15:10,493
Come on,
just one little swallow.

340
00:15:10,576 --> 00:15:11,786
If you say it's cider,
it's cider.

341
00:15:11,869 --> 00:15:13,329
Please,
Dr. Charles.

342
00:15:13,413 --> 00:15:14,956
Oh, well.

343
00:15:18,459 --> 00:15:20,586
Why, Nick,
this is cider.

344
00:15:23,881 --> 00:15:26,426
Oh, what a dinner.
What a dinner.

345
00:15:26,509 --> 00:15:28,886
Mmm! Ha ha!

346
00:15:28,970 --> 00:15:30,805
Oh, ma, I'm glad to see
that you still have

347
00:15:30,888 --> 00:15:33,808
that same old magic touch
with the skillet.

348
00:15:33,891 --> 00:15:35,226
Nora: It was
delicious, mother.

349
00:15:35,309 --> 00:15:36,811
Oh, it was just sort
of thrown together.

350
00:15:36,894 --> 00:15:38,521
Sure. Just
thrown together.

351
00:15:38,604 --> 00:15:40,273
She's been over that stove
for hours.

352
00:15:40,356 --> 00:15:42,525
Now, don't pay any
attention to him, Nick.

353
00:15:42,608 --> 00:15:45,194
Hilda, bring
the coffee in here.

354
00:15:46,529 --> 00:15:47,655
Well, dad,
that certainly is

355
00:15:47,738 --> 00:15:49,073
fine news
about the hospital.

356
00:15:49,157 --> 00:15:51,617
Yes. Sam Ronson's going
to make a recommendation

357
00:15:51,701 --> 00:15:53,202
at the next meeting
of the board,

358
00:15:53,286 --> 00:15:54,829
and a recommendation
from him

359
00:15:54,912 --> 00:15:56,289
is as good
as an order.

360
00:15:56,372 --> 00:15:57,331
Nora:
Who's Sam Ronson?

361
00:15:57,415 --> 00:15:58,875
He's the town banker.

362
00:15:58,958 --> 00:16:00,418
He has a hand in everything
that goes on here.

363
00:16:00,501 --> 00:16:02,545
I suppose he's what
you'd call a typhoon.

364
00:16:02,628 --> 00:16:04,422
Don't you mean
tycoon, mother?

365
00:16:04,505 --> 00:16:06,716
Typhoon is a sort
of a big wind.

366
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:08,342
Well, that's
Sam Ronson.

367
00:16:08,426 --> 00:16:09,844
[chuckles]

368
00:16:09,927 --> 00:16:11,846
Nick, tell us something
about your work

369
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:13,306
in New York.

370
00:16:13,389 --> 00:16:14,557
Nora:
Yes, Nick, do.

371
00:16:14,640 --> 00:16:15,892
Have you
gone to work?

372
00:16:15,975 --> 00:16:17,477
What are you
doing?

373
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:19,520
Oh, same old thing.

374
00:16:19,604 --> 00:16:21,772
Oh, so you're
still a policeman?

375
00:16:24,108 --> 00:16:27,236
Well, I'd hardly
put it that way.

376
00:16:27,320 --> 00:16:29,030
No. How would
you put it?

377
00:16:29,113 --> 00:16:31,824
I'd say that Nick
was more of a genius.

378
00:16:31,908 --> 00:16:33,493
My Nick?

379
00:16:34,202 --> 00:16:35,620
You see,

380
00:16:35,703 --> 00:16:36,996
Nick doesn't actually
work with the police.

381
00:16:37,079 --> 00:16:38,456
In fact, people
call on him

382
00:16:38,539 --> 00:16:40,333
who think he's better
than the police.

383
00:16:40,416 --> 00:16:41,751
He's paid
very large fees

384
00:16:41,834 --> 00:16:42,835
because his work
is important,

385
00:16:42,919 --> 00:16:44,378
extremely important.

386
00:16:44,462 --> 00:16:46,589
My dear Nora, I didn't say
it wasn't important.

387
00:16:46,672 --> 00:16:47,757
You implied
that you didn't think

388
00:16:47,840 --> 00:16:49,008
it was
very important.

389
00:16:49,091 --> 00:16:50,426
You gave the impression
that you thought

390
00:16:50,510 --> 00:16:52,136
that Nick walked up
and down the street

391
00:16:52,220 --> 00:16:53,387
swinging a club.

392
00:16:53,471 --> 00:16:54,764
Oh, well, if i gave
that impression,

393
00:16:54,847 --> 00:16:55,932
I'm heartily sorry.

394
00:16:56,015 --> 00:16:57,099
Oh, sure.

395
00:16:57,183 --> 00:16:58,935
A very handsome apology.

396
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:01,062
If Nick thinks it's important
to be a policeman,

397
00:17:01,145 --> 00:17:03,064
that's all that
matters... I suppose.

398
00:17:03,147 --> 00:17:04,565
But you don't know
what he does...

399
00:17:04,649 --> 00:17:07,401
Darling, why don't you
pop out to the kitchen

400
00:17:07,485 --> 00:17:09,320
and speed up
the coffee, hmm?

401
00:17:09,403 --> 00:17:10,613
Some of the cases
Nick has solved

402
00:17:10,696 --> 00:17:12,281
were considered
absolutely impossible.

403
00:17:12,365 --> 00:17:13,491
Darling,
let me show you

404
00:17:13,574 --> 00:17:14,825
the view from
the front porch.

405
00:17:14,909 --> 00:17:16,327
Oh, it's beautiful
in the moonlight.

406
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:17,578
What about
the Wynant murder

407
00:17:17,662 --> 00:17:18,788
or the fingers
O'Toole case

408
00:17:18,871 --> 00:17:20,373
or the slaughterhouse
mystery?

409
00:17:20,456 --> 00:17:22,041
Or take
Stinky Davis.

410
00:17:22,124 --> 00:17:23,501
Who's Stinky Davis?

411
00:17:23,584 --> 00:17:24,752
Stinky Davis?

412
00:17:24,835 --> 00:17:26,671
The Stinky Davis
case illustrates

413
00:17:26,754 --> 00:17:27,838
what i mean
about Nick.

414
00:17:27,922 --> 00:17:30,007
Yes, I'm sure
it does, Nora.

415
00:17:30,091 --> 00:17:31,384
Do you still
take two lumps

416
00:17:31,467 --> 00:17:32,760
in your stinky...
I mean, in your coffee?

417
00:17:35,221 --> 00:17:36,389
Just imagine...

418
00:17:36,472 --> 00:17:37,974
four murders,
all strangulation,

419
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:39,642
no fingerprints,
no clues.

420
00:17:39,725 --> 00:17:40,726
The police
were baffled.

421
00:17:40,810 --> 00:17:41,936
Yes, of course.

422
00:17:42,019 --> 00:17:43,020
All they had
were four bodies.

423
00:17:43,104 --> 00:17:44,480
So, what
did they do?

424
00:17:44,564 --> 00:17:45,856
They dumped the whole
thing in Nick's lap.

425
00:17:45,940 --> 00:17:47,316
I see.

426
00:17:47,400 --> 00:17:49,235
Nobody
suspected Stinky

427
00:17:49,318 --> 00:17:50,486
because
he'd been a cripple

428
00:17:50,570 --> 00:17:51,946
ever since
some nitro went off

429
00:17:52,029 --> 00:17:54,031
while he was cracking
a canister in Salt Lake.

430
00:17:54,115 --> 00:17:55,825
Everybody thought it was
Rainbow Benny,

431
00:17:55,908 --> 00:17:57,285
but Nick knew
that Rainbow

432
00:17:57,368 --> 00:17:58,911
was an expert
with the shiv.

433
00:17:58,995 --> 00:18:00,788
Strangling was
out of his line.

434
00:18:00,871 --> 00:18:02,665
Oh. Smart Nick.

435
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:04,709
Then they turned the heat
on Slasher Martin,

436
00:18:04,792 --> 00:18:06,252
who ran a dice joint
down in Chinatown,

437
00:18:06,335 --> 00:18:07,587
but Slasher
had an alibi

438
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:08,921
with Squinty Burke
and Studsy Greene,

439
00:18:09,005 --> 00:18:10,590
so that
took care of him.

440
00:18:10,673 --> 00:18:12,842
But all the time,
Nick was certain

441
00:18:12,925 --> 00:18:15,052
that Stinky Davis
was the Killer.

442
00:18:15,136 --> 00:18:18,264
Why? Because he had
him pegged right away

443
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:21,726
for a two-timing,
double-crossing rat.

444
00:18:21,809 --> 00:18:23,102
Nora: Would the police
listen to Nick?

445
00:18:23,185 --> 00:18:25,479
No. They told him it was
a Hophead theory,

446
00:18:25,563 --> 00:18:27,148
wild as loco buttons,

447
00:18:27,231 --> 00:18:28,566
because Stinky
was a cripple

448
00:18:28,649 --> 00:18:30,693
and couldn't navigate.

449
00:18:30,776 --> 00:18:32,445
So, Nick got the brush-off
from the police.

450
00:18:32,528 --> 00:18:34,113
They cold-shouldered
him right out,

451
00:18:34,196 --> 00:18:35,615
but did that
stop him?

452
00:18:35,698 --> 00:18:37,742
Nora: No, sir. He knew
the case was hot,

453
00:18:37,825 --> 00:18:38,993
and he was all set

454
00:18:39,076 --> 00:18:40,119
to start cooking
on the front burner.

455
00:18:40,202 --> 00:18:41,537
He said, "Stinky,

456
00:18:41,621 --> 00:18:43,497
"you're the two-timing,
double-crossing rat

457
00:18:43,581 --> 00:18:45,583
"who strangled
Knobs McLure and Greasy Joe

458
00:18:45,666 --> 00:18:47,209
and Horsefaced Dan
and Denver Mike."

459
00:18:47,293 --> 00:18:49,670
And then he turned
his back on him,

460
00:18:49,754 --> 00:18:51,172
and the trick worked,

461
00:18:51,255 --> 00:18:53,090
because Stinky got up
out of his wheelchair

462
00:18:53,174 --> 00:18:54,925
and tried to strangle Nick
with a piece of wire

463
00:18:55,009 --> 00:18:56,302
he had hidden
in his mouth,

464
00:18:56,385 --> 00:18:58,387
but just in time,
Nick turned around,

465
00:18:58,471 --> 00:19:00,181
gave him
the old one-two,

466
00:19:00,264 --> 00:19:02,600
and knocked Stinky colder
than an ice flounder.

467
00:19:02,683 --> 00:19:03,851
Whew.

468
00:19:03,934 --> 00:19:05,269
Stinky wasn't
a cripple at all.

469
00:19:05,353 --> 00:19:07,104
He was just using it
to cover up his crimes.

470
00:19:07,188 --> 00:19:09,523
Now, what do you
think of that?

471
00:19:09,607 --> 00:19:11,192
Well, if Nick
suspected

472
00:19:11,275 --> 00:19:12,693
that Stinky
wasn't a cripple,

473
00:19:12,777 --> 00:19:15,029
why didn't he have him
examined by a doctor?

474
00:19:15,112 --> 00:19:17,239
The whole thing's
so silly.

475
00:19:17,323 --> 00:19:19,533
Dr. Charles...

476
00:19:19,617 --> 00:19:21,369
you are impossible.

477
00:19:21,452 --> 00:19:22,995
Now, you see?

478
00:19:23,079 --> 00:19:24,789
You've
upset her.

479
00:19:24,872 --> 00:19:26,332
[chuckles]

480
00:19:26,415 --> 00:19:28,209
Spirited little thing,
isn't she?

481
00:19:28,292 --> 00:19:31,712
Mm-hmm. Well, you know
how women are.

482
00:19:31,796 --> 00:19:33,631
No. How are they?

483
00:19:36,217 --> 00:19:37,426
[chuckles]

484
00:19:41,263 --> 00:19:43,557
Mother, come here.

485
00:19:49,271 --> 00:19:50,231
Nora: Isn't he beautiful?

486
00:19:50,314 --> 00:19:52,149
[laughing]

487
00:19:53,901 --> 00:19:54,985
Mother,
what's wrong

488
00:19:55,069 --> 00:19:56,445
between Nick
and his father?

489
00:19:56,529 --> 00:19:57,863
Well, hasn't Nick
ever told you?

490
00:19:57,947 --> 00:19:59,448
No. He's very seldom
talked about it.

491
00:19:59,532 --> 00:20:00,825
Well, it seems
rather silly,

492
00:20:00,908 --> 00:20:02,076
but the doctor
had his heart set

493
00:20:02,159 --> 00:20:03,411
upon Nick becoming
a doctor, too,

494
00:20:03,494 --> 00:20:04,578
so that they could
work together.

495
00:20:04,662 --> 00:20:05,746
That's how
the whole idea

496
00:20:05,830 --> 00:20:07,331
for the hospital
first started,

497
00:20:07,415 --> 00:20:08,791
but Nick had
a mind of his own.

498
00:20:08,874 --> 00:20:09,917
And became
a policeman.

499
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:11,544
Yes. That's
about it.

500
00:20:11,627 --> 00:20:12,920
I wish he could
do something

501
00:20:13,003 --> 00:20:15,172
to impress his father
while he's here.

502
00:20:15,256 --> 00:20:16,924
I don't suppose there's
any crime in Sycamore Springs?

503
00:20:17,007 --> 00:20:18,217
Gracious, no.

504
00:20:18,300 --> 00:20:19,468
The only excitement
we ever had

505
00:20:19,552 --> 00:20:21,512
was a runaway horse
last Christmas.

506
00:20:21,595 --> 00:20:23,013
There's nothing in the world
Nick wants more

507
00:20:23,097 --> 00:20:24,724
than a pat on the back
from his father.

508
00:20:24,807 --> 00:20:26,308
If he got that, I think
he'd pop a vest button.

509
00:20:26,392 --> 00:20:27,393
Did he admit that?

510
00:20:27,476 --> 00:20:29,353
No.
You know Nicky.

511
00:20:29,437 --> 00:20:30,563
We were married
three years

512
00:20:30,646 --> 00:20:31,981
before he told me
he loved me.

513
00:20:32,064 --> 00:20:33,566
Well, all
i can say is,

514
00:20:33,649 --> 00:20:35,192
if you're looking for crime
in Sycamore Springs,

515
00:20:35,276 --> 00:20:36,861
you'll have to
commit it yourself.

516
00:20:36,944 --> 00:20:39,405
I wonder...
Nicky always says

517
00:20:39,488 --> 00:20:41,574
that there's a skeleton
in nearly every closet,

518
00:20:41,657 --> 00:20:42,950
and if you rattle
it hard enough,

519
00:20:43,033 --> 00:20:44,368
something
always happens.

520
00:20:44,452 --> 00:20:45,953
But would Nick
like it

521
00:20:46,036 --> 00:20:48,038
if you went around rattling
people's skeletons?

522
00:20:48,122 --> 00:20:49,582
Oh, he'd be furious,

523
00:20:49,665 --> 00:20:51,250
but if some crime
did break,

524
00:20:51,333 --> 00:20:52,460
it would be
a wonderful chance

525
00:20:52,543 --> 00:20:53,627
for him to show
his father

526
00:20:53,711 --> 00:20:56,046
what a great
detective he is.

527
00:20:56,130 --> 00:20:57,548
Hmm.

528
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:05,139
Studying hard,
Junior?

529
00:21:07,183 --> 00:21:08,350
Hmm?

530
00:21:09,643 --> 00:21:11,228
Hmm?

531
00:21:11,312 --> 00:21:14,064
Ha ha. Oh, hi.

532
00:21:14,148 --> 00:21:15,274
Ahh.

533
00:21:15,357 --> 00:21:18,110
Guess i must have
dropped off.

534
00:21:18,194 --> 00:21:19,361
Would you like
to lie here?

535
00:21:19,445 --> 00:21:21,197
No, no. Stay
where you are.

536
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:22,448
I don't want to
disturb you

537
00:21:22,531 --> 00:21:24,784
while you"re working
on your lessons.

538
00:21:24,867 --> 00:21:28,287
I'll pull up one
of these chairs.

539
00:21:28,370 --> 00:21:29,872
Can't i help you?

540
00:21:29,955 --> 00:21:32,958
No. You've made
enough effort.

541
00:21:34,126 --> 00:21:35,711
Hmm.

542
00:21:35,795 --> 00:21:37,171
I was just thinking
about a little gal

543
00:21:37,254 --> 00:21:40,090
by the name
of Alice Brody.

544
00:21:41,926 --> 00:21:43,761
We used to come out here
on hot summer nights

545
00:21:43,844 --> 00:21:45,930
and play
on her banjo.

546
00:21:46,013 --> 00:21:47,264
Oh?

547
00:21:48,682 --> 00:21:50,893
The boys used to
write their names on it.

548
00:21:54,188 --> 00:21:56,982
She married a brewer
from Milwaukee.

549
00:21:57,066 --> 00:21:59,819
What did he play,
the bull fiddle?

550
00:21:59,902 --> 00:22:02,363
Nick: Oh. No, she was
very fond of beer.

551
00:22:04,365 --> 00:22:05,825
Are you sure i can't
help you with that?

552
00:22:05,908 --> 00:22:09,995
No. No. You might
get all sweaty and die.

553
00:22:12,122 --> 00:22:14,375
[slurping]

554
00:22:16,085 --> 00:22:17,795
Man: Well,
hello there.

555
00:22:17,878 --> 00:22:19,171
Hmm?

556
00:22:19,255 --> 00:22:21,257
Nick, you old
son of a gun.

557
00:22:21,340 --> 00:22:25,094
Why didn't you let me know
you were in town?

558
00:22:25,177 --> 00:22:26,637
Oh, hello,
Bruce.

559
00:22:26,720 --> 00:22:28,681
Hello, Nick. Well, it looks
like the old days.

560
00:22:28,764 --> 00:22:30,224
Yeah. Ha ha!

561
00:22:30,307 --> 00:22:32,560
Oh, uh, darling,
meet an old schoolmate...

562
00:22:32,643 --> 00:22:33,769
Bruce Clayworth.
Mrs. Charles.

563
00:22:33,853 --> 00:22:34,937
How do you do,
Mr. Clayworth?

564
00:22:35,020 --> 00:22:36,313
How do you do,
Mrs. Charles?

565
00:22:36,397 --> 00:22:37,731
Well, I'm certainly
glad to meet you.

566
00:22:37,815 --> 00:22:40,860
Now i know the secret
of Nick's success.

567
00:22:40,943 --> 00:22:42,611
Yes, if it weren't
for her money,

568
00:22:42,695 --> 00:22:45,072
I probably would have had to
go to work, like you, Bruce.

569
00:22:45,155 --> 00:22:46,866
What do you do,
Mr. Clayworth?

570
00:22:46,949 --> 00:22:48,284
Oh, I'm just
a small-town doctor.

571
00:22:48,367 --> 00:22:49,451
Always will be, I guess.

572
00:22:49,535 --> 00:22:51,078
Nick had
the right idea...

573
00:22:51,161 --> 00:22:52,830
get out where the money is,
and it'll come to you.

574
00:22:52,913 --> 00:22:54,874
- That's what he always said.
- Did i say that?

575
00:22:54,957 --> 00:22:57,501
Well, he was always the smart
one anyway, Mrs. Charles.

576
00:22:57,585 --> 00:22:59,670
What are you doing now, Nick?
You here on a case?

577
00:22:59,753 --> 00:23:02,047
No, no, no. We're
just visiting the folks.

578
00:23:02,131 --> 00:23:04,258
Let's see something of you
while you're in town, huh?

579
00:23:04,341 --> 00:23:06,010
I got to run along.
I'm going to have a baby.

580
00:23:06,093 --> 00:23:07,386
Drink plenty of milk.

581
00:23:07,469 --> 00:23:09,972
Oh, not me.
Down at the hospit...

582
00:23:10,055 --> 00:23:12,016
he was always a clown,
Mrs. Charles.

583
00:23:12,099 --> 00:23:14,351
He used to put us
in stitches. Good-bye.

584
00:23:14,435 --> 00:23:16,103
- Good-bye.
- Good-bye.

585
00:23:17,855 --> 00:23:20,608
How would you like to put me
in stitches, papa?

586
00:23:22,318 --> 00:23:24,820
Hmm.

587
00:23:24,904 --> 00:23:26,822
Ahh...

588
00:23:26,906 --> 00:23:29,366
Woman: Well, if it isn't
little Nicholas Charles.

589
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:32,411
Nick: Huh?

590
00:23:32,494 --> 00:23:33,746
[softly]
Old home week.

591
00:23:35,164 --> 00:23:37,291
Oh, it's Mrs. Peavy,
isn't it?

592
00:23:38,876 --> 00:23:40,961
Hmm...

593
00:23:41,045 --> 00:23:42,504
Nick: Well, hello.

594
00:23:42,588 --> 00:23:44,548
You've grown.

595
00:23:44,632 --> 00:23:47,384
Yes.
In all directions.

596
00:23:47,468 --> 00:23:49,178
You remember
my young nephew, Willoughby.

597
00:23:49,261 --> 00:23:50,763
Oh, yes, of course.
How are you?

598
00:23:50,846 --> 00:23:51,889
How do you do?

599
00:23:51,972 --> 00:23:53,724
He seems to have
grown, too.

600
00:23:53,807 --> 00:23:55,976
And i suppose
this is Mrs. Charles.

601
00:23:56,060 --> 00:23:57,645
Yes.
I'm Mrs. Charles.

602
00:23:57,728 --> 00:23:59,021
Oh, I'm so sorry.

603
00:23:59,104 --> 00:24:00,981
This is my
old schoolteacher Miss Peavy

604
00:24:01,065 --> 00:24:02,566
and Willoughby Peavy.

605
00:24:02,650 --> 00:24:04,944
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

606
00:24:05,027 --> 00:24:07,279
Willoughby is working
out at the plant now.

607
00:24:07,363 --> 00:24:10,324
Are you in town
on a case, Nicholas?

608
00:24:10,407 --> 00:24:12,660
No. I'm just trying
to get a little rest.

609
00:24:12,743 --> 00:24:14,703
I daresay there's
plenty of evil

610
00:24:14,787 --> 00:24:16,163
in Sycamore Springs,

611
00:24:16,246 --> 00:24:18,707
and it's your duty
to ferret it out.

612
00:24:18,791 --> 00:24:21,001
Oh, ha ha.
Well, I daresay.

613
00:24:21,085 --> 00:24:22,753
Hew to the line.

614
00:24:22,836 --> 00:24:25,172
Let the chips fall
where they may.

615
00:24:25,255 --> 00:24:26,256
[barking]

616
00:24:26,340 --> 00:24:29,051
Asta. Asta.
Asta, no.

617
00:24:29,134 --> 00:24:31,929
What a nasty
little dog.

618
00:24:32,012 --> 00:24:33,013
Come along,
Willoughby.

619
00:24:33,097 --> 00:24:34,556
Oh, don't
hurry away.

620
00:24:34,640 --> 00:24:37,267
I hope i see you
again, Mrs. Charles...

621
00:24:37,351 --> 00:24:38,894
without your dog.

622
00:24:38,978 --> 00:24:41,438
[growling]

623
00:24:41,522 --> 00:24:43,899
Darling, is that
why you burned

624
00:24:43,983 --> 00:24:45,818
the schoolhouse
down?

625
00:24:45,901 --> 00:24:47,194
What did you want to
shoot your mouth off

626
00:24:47,277 --> 00:24:48,320
about me for?

627
00:24:48,404 --> 00:24:49,822
Oh, hush up.
I just told them

628
00:24:49,905 --> 00:24:51,198
you were working
at the plant.

629
00:24:51,281 --> 00:24:52,741
I didn't tell them
what you were doing.

630
00:25:03,460 --> 00:25:05,295
Having trouble
with that?

631
00:25:34,116 --> 00:25:35,993
Very funny,
I'm sure.

632
00:25:38,537 --> 00:25:39,580
Oh!

633
00:25:39,663 --> 00:25:40,831
[laughing]

634
00:25:45,461 --> 00:25:47,671
Mother: Children.

635
00:25:47,755 --> 00:25:49,256
[laughter stops]

636
00:25:51,633 --> 00:25:52,801
Hello, mother.

637
00:25:54,887 --> 00:25:57,431
I saw all those people
stopping, Nicky.

638
00:25:57,514 --> 00:25:59,850
You're getting to be
quite a public character.

639
00:25:59,933 --> 00:26:02,019
Yes. I feel like
a public something.

640
00:26:04,313 --> 00:26:05,939
It's funny.
They all assume

641
00:26:06,023 --> 00:26:07,649
he's working
on a case.

642
00:26:11,487 --> 00:26:12,821
Woman: Mind if i come in?

643
00:26:12,905 --> 00:26:15,032
Not at all, Laurabel.
Come along.

644
00:26:17,242 --> 00:26:18,994
- Don't be long.
- No.

645
00:26:19,078 --> 00:26:20,162
Who's this?

646
00:26:20,245 --> 00:26:21,371
It's Laurabel Ronson.

647
00:26:21,455 --> 00:26:22,706
She's the daughter
of that typhoon

648
00:26:22,790 --> 00:26:24,416
i was telling
you about.

649
00:26:24,500 --> 00:26:26,293
You're Mrs. Charles,
aren't you?

650
00:26:26,376 --> 00:26:27,377
Yes.

651
00:26:27,461 --> 00:26:28,545
Oh, I knew it.
I knew it

652
00:26:28,629 --> 00:26:29,671
when i saw you
from the car.

653
00:26:29,755 --> 00:26:31,882
I felt it
here, inside.

654
00:26:31,965 --> 00:26:33,634
Laurabel goes
to dramatic school.

655
00:26:33,717 --> 00:26:34,968
Oh, I see.

656
00:26:35,052 --> 00:26:36,595
And this is your
famous husband.

657
00:26:36,678 --> 00:26:38,555
Nora: Yes. He
looks alright

658
00:26:38,639 --> 00:26:40,641
when you get him
dressed up.

659
00:26:40,724 --> 00:26:42,059
You're here
on a mystery,

660
00:26:42,142 --> 00:26:44,186
a deep, deep mystery
in Sycamore Springs.

661
00:26:44,269 --> 00:26:47,189
I feel it
here, inside.

662
00:26:47,272 --> 00:26:48,690
Well, I'm sorry
to disagree

663
00:26:48,774 --> 00:26:50,651
with your insides,
miss, uh...

664
00:26:50,734 --> 00:26:52,152
Just call me
Laurabel.

665
00:26:52,236 --> 00:26:53,695
[stammering]

666
00:26:53,779 --> 00:26:56,115
But i'm really just here
for a little rest.

667
00:26:56,198 --> 00:26:57,950
Mother: You must
pardon Nick, Laurabel.

668
00:26:58,033 --> 00:26:59,159
He's been working
very hard in the city,

669
00:26:59,243 --> 00:27:00,619
and he's tired.

670
00:27:00,702 --> 00:27:02,204
Oh, yes, I know how
these geniuses are...

671
00:27:02,287 --> 00:27:03,580
all nerves.

672
00:27:03,664 --> 00:27:04,915
But i realize you
can't talk about it,

673
00:27:04,998 --> 00:27:06,542
even if he is
here on a case.

674
00:27:06,625 --> 00:27:08,752
No. We mustn't
talk about it.

675
00:27:08,836 --> 00:27:10,420
In fact,
we don't have to.

676
00:27:10,504 --> 00:27:12,965
Everything is so frightfully
hush-hush these days,

677
00:27:13,048 --> 00:27:16,009
but i know, and i think
it's wonderful.

678
00:27:16,093 --> 00:27:17,427
[horn honks]

679
00:27:17,511 --> 00:27:19,054
Good gracious. Who's making
all that racket?

680
00:27:19,138 --> 00:27:20,389
[honking horn]

681
00:27:20,472 --> 00:27:23,308
Oh, that's
Tom Clayworth.

682
00:27:23,392 --> 00:27:24,685
I promised to drive him
to the train.

683
00:27:24,768 --> 00:27:26,228
He's leaving for Boston.

684
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:27,938
Oh. Has he got his discharge
from the army yet?

685
00:27:28,021 --> 00:27:29,273
Yes, but ever since
he came back

686
00:27:29,356 --> 00:27:30,482
from the south seas,

687
00:27:30,566 --> 00:27:31,817
he's been
as nervous as a cat.

688
00:27:31,900 --> 00:27:32,985
Mother: Poor boy.

689
00:27:33,068 --> 00:27:34,528
And so jealous.

690
00:27:34,611 --> 00:27:37,781
Why, he won't even let
another man talk to me.

691
00:27:37,865 --> 00:27:39,491
I haven't said
anything.

692
00:27:39,575 --> 00:27:41,034
I must take
my leave now,

693
00:27:41,118 --> 00:27:42,536
but we're going to see
a lot of each other.

694
00:27:42,619 --> 00:27:45,289
I'm sure.
I feel it here...

695
00:27:45,372 --> 00:27:46,790
Inside?

696
00:27:46,874 --> 00:27:48,167
Yes.

697
00:27:50,502 --> 00:27:52,045
And don't forget,
Laurabel,

698
00:27:52,129 --> 00:27:53,463
we mustn't
talk about it.

699
00:27:53,547 --> 00:27:55,174
Oh, I understand,
Mrs. Charles,

700
00:27:55,257 --> 00:27:58,218
and your secret
couldn't be in better hands.

701
00:27:58,302 --> 00:28:00,220
[instrumental music]

702
00:28:14,902 --> 00:28:16,570
But it's all over
town, Mrs. Charles,

703
00:28:16,653 --> 00:28:18,155
that Mr. Charles
is here on a case.

704
00:28:18,238 --> 00:28:20,073
If you can only give me
a little statement.

705
00:28:20,157 --> 00:28:22,534
I never discuss
Mr. Charles' activities.

706
00:28:22,618 --> 00:28:24,620
He happens
to be out now,

707
00:28:24,703 --> 00:28:27,497
but Mr. Charles
is in town,

708
00:28:27,581 --> 00:28:29,541
Mr. Charles
is a detective,

709
00:28:29,625 --> 00:28:32,294
and you can draw
your own conclusions.

710
00:28:32,377 --> 00:28:33,795
Thank you!

711
00:28:36,924 --> 00:28:38,717
"In an exclusive interview
with Mrs. Charles

712
00:28:38,800 --> 00:28:40,302
"by the Sycamore Springs
"Evening News,"

713
00:28:40,385 --> 00:28:42,137
"she raised
an eyebrow and said,

714
00:28:42,221 --> 00:28:44,348
"I never discuss
Mr. Charles' activities

715
00:28:44,431 --> 00:28:46,475
but you can draw your
own conclusions.”

716
00:28:46,558 --> 00:28:48,060
Now, that's
a lot of malarkey.

717
00:28:48,143 --> 00:28:50,354
Why, I've known
Nick Charles for years.

718
00:28:50,437 --> 00:28:52,064
If there was anything
going on in this town,

719
00:28:52,147 --> 00:28:53,815
he'd be the first
to let me know.

720
00:28:55,400 --> 00:28:57,569
Look at that.
Nick Charles is in town.

721
00:28:57,653 --> 00:28:59,154
The paper says he's here
on some investigation.

722
00:28:59,238 --> 00:29:00,489
That means
he's after us.

723
00:29:00,572 --> 00:29:01,657
We got to
get that painting

724
00:29:01,740 --> 00:29:02,908
and get out of here.

725
00:29:02,991 --> 00:29:04,076
But the painting
hasn't come in yet.

726
00:29:04,159 --> 00:29:05,535
I was at Crump's
this morning.

727
00:29:05,619 --> 00:29:07,412
I can't
understand that.

728
00:29:07,496 --> 00:29:08,622
Are you sure
you asked Crump

729
00:29:08,705 --> 00:29:09,748
for the painting
of the windmill?

730
00:29:09,831 --> 00:29:10,916
Of course i'm sure.

731
00:29:10,999 --> 00:29:12,251
Well, then, why...

732
00:29:12,334 --> 00:29:15,295
Now, Edgar, calm down.
We'll get it.

733
00:29:15,379 --> 00:29:16,838
I don't like
that flatfoot

734
00:29:16,922 --> 00:29:18,465
<i>snooping
around town.</i>

735
00:29:23,637 --> 00:29:24,805
We'll go
down there now.

736
00:29:24,888 --> 00:29:26,598
Alright,
alright, alright.

737
00:29:45,409 --> 00:29:47,244
Mister?

738
00:29:47,327 --> 00:29:49,121
Huh? Oh,
how do you do?

739
00:29:49,204 --> 00:29:50,247
How much is this?

740
00:29:50,330 --> 00:29:52,040
This? Oh, you
don't want this.

741
00:29:52,124 --> 00:29:53,792
Oh, gracious me, no.

742
00:29:53,875 --> 00:29:54,960
But i do want it.

743
00:29:55,043 --> 00:29:56,211
No, no.
I can't sell that.

744
00:29:56,295 --> 00:29:57,629
That's by one
of our local boys.

745
00:29:57,713 --> 00:29:59,047
It just came in.

746
00:29:59,131 --> 00:30:01,508
I have a standing offer
for all of his work.

747
00:30:01,591 --> 00:30:04,136
Some crazy woman
thinks he's a genius.

748
00:30:04,219 --> 00:30:06,054
But i happen
to like it.

749
00:30:06,138 --> 00:30:07,764
That old windmill
has a certain

750
00:30:07,848 --> 00:30:09,766
sentimental association
for my husband,

751
00:30:09,850 --> 00:30:10,976
and i'd like to
give it to him

752
00:30:11,059 --> 00:30:12,602
for his birthday
tomorrow.

753
00:30:12,686 --> 00:30:14,271
How much did
the other woman pay you?

754
00:30:14,354 --> 00:30:16,815
$50. She buys
all of his work.

755
00:30:16,898 --> 00:30:18,108
I'll give you 60.

756
00:30:18,191 --> 00:30:20,319
I beg your...pardon?

757
00:30:20,402 --> 00:30:21,903
I said
I'd give you $60.

758
00:30:21,987 --> 00:30:23,196
But you'll never
make any money

759
00:30:23,280 --> 00:30:25,741
paying $60
for a $50 painting.

760
00:30:25,824 --> 00:30:28,702
But i don't want
to make any money.

761
00:30:28,785 --> 00:30:30,287
My husband spent
his whole youth

762
00:30:30,370 --> 00:30:31,496
in that windmill,

763
00:30:31,580 --> 00:30:32,873
and he's sentimental
about it.

764
00:30:32,956 --> 00:30:34,082
Tomorrow
is his birthday.

765
00:30:34,166 --> 00:30:35,417
Can't you
understand that?

766
00:30:35,500 --> 00:30:36,585
<i>Yes, but i
promised her.</i>

767
00:30:36,668 --> 00:30:38,086
She'd be awfully
mad at me.

768
00:30:38,170 --> 00:30:39,421
Oh, don't worry
about that.

769
00:30:39,504 --> 00:30:41,757
Yes, but i like
to keep my promises...

770
00:30:41,840 --> 00:30:42,799
if i can.

771
00:30:42,883 --> 00:30:44,217
10, 50...

772
00:30:44,301 --> 00:30:46,386
I wish i'd gone into
some other business.

773
00:30:46,470 --> 00:30:48,513
60.
There you are.

774
00:30:50,307 --> 00:30:52,309
Oh, don't worry
about that.

775
00:30:52,392 --> 00:30:53,935
Thank you.
Good day.

776
00:30:54,019 --> 00:30:55,771
Good day.
And happy birthday.

777
00:31:01,568 --> 00:31:02,861
Has it come in yet?

778
00:31:02,944 --> 00:31:04,613
Yes? Has what
come in yet?

779
00:31:04,696 --> 00:31:06,031
The painting.

780
00:31:06,114 --> 00:31:08,617
Painting? Oh, I have
a lot of paintings.

781
00:31:08,700 --> 00:31:12,079
There's the "Barefoot Boy,"
"The Stag at Dawn,”

782
00:31:12,162 --> 00:31:14,039
and "Waiting for
the Robert E. Lee,"

783
00:31:14,122 --> 00:31:15,540
and all of them bad.

784
00:31:15,624 --> 00:31:17,918
No, no, no.
Don't you remember me?

785
00:31:18,001 --> 00:31:19,920
I'm the woman
who collects Bertons.

786
00:31:20,003 --> 00:31:22,422
You were expecting
another one in today.

787
00:31:22,506 --> 00:31:26,385
Oh, that. Well,
I just sold it.

788
00:31:26,468 --> 00:31:27,844
Sold it?

789
00:31:27,928 --> 00:31:29,262
To whom?

790
00:31:29,346 --> 00:31:32,432
That woman who was just
in here with a birthday.

791
00:31:32,516 --> 00:31:33,975
Oh!

792
00:31:34,059 --> 00:31:36,103
You...
you old fool!

793
00:31:37,729 --> 00:31:39,147
I knew she'd
be mad at me.

794
00:31:40,357 --> 00:31:41,358
There goes
your painting.

795
00:31:43,610 --> 00:31:45,112
Well, somebody's
going to pay plenty

796
00:31:45,195 --> 00:31:47,239
for that picture
before we're through,

797
00:31:47,322 --> 00:31:49,199
and it isn't
going to be me.

798
00:31:57,916 --> 00:31:59,835
Oh, good evening,
Willoughby.

799
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:01,044
Mr. Charles.

800
00:32:01,128 --> 00:32:02,879
You, uh, looking
for clues?

801
00:32:02,963 --> 00:32:04,631
Oh. No, I'm not,

802
00:32:04,714 --> 00:32:06,758
but my pup seems
to have found something.

803
00:32:07,509 --> 00:32:09,594
Yeah.

804
00:32:09,678 --> 00:32:11,388
Well...

805
00:32:14,766 --> 00:32:16,184
Come on, Asta.

806
00:32:16,268 --> 00:32:18,979
You've had enough botany
for one night.

807
00:32:26,695 --> 00:32:29,364
"I never discuss
Mr. Charles' activities.

808
00:32:31,241 --> 00:32:33,368
You can draw
your own conclusions.”

809
00:32:35,162 --> 00:32:36,621
Hmm...

810
00:32:42,252 --> 00:32:44,838
Oh, there
you are.

811
00:32:46,173 --> 00:32:48,425
I thought you were
never coming.

812
00:32:48,508 --> 00:32:50,051
Something happened?

813
00:32:50,135 --> 00:32:51,303
Nothing.

814
00:32:51,386 --> 00:32:53,180
I'm just glad to
see you. That's all.

815
00:32:53,263 --> 00:32:55,515
Oh, well, has papa's
little hunchy-punchy-bunchy

816
00:32:55,599 --> 00:32:57,184
been having
a busy time?

817
00:32:57,267 --> 00:32:58,435
Well, I...

818
00:32:58,518 --> 00:33:00,770
We mustn't tire
ourselves out, must we?

819
00:33:00,854 --> 00:33:02,898
What have you got
behind your back?

820
00:33:02,981 --> 00:33:04,191
Hmm?

821
00:33:04,274 --> 00:33:05,984
Oh, the paper.

822
00:33:06,067 --> 00:33:07,777
I couldn't find it.

823
00:33:07,861 --> 00:33:11,072
Father, does
the old woodshed still stand

824
00:33:11,156 --> 00:33:13,742
in its sheltered nook
amongst the trees?

825
00:33:13,825 --> 00:33:15,035
Father: Yes, Nick.

826
00:33:15,118 --> 00:33:17,996
Mm-hmm. And does
the trusty razor strop

827
00:33:18,079 --> 00:33:19,915
still hang
behind the door?

828
00:33:19,998 --> 00:33:22,209
No. I use
an electric razor now.

829
00:33:22,292 --> 00:33:24,169
Oh, oh.

830
00:33:24,252 --> 00:33:27,339
Well, necessity is
the mother of invention.

831
00:33:27,422 --> 00:33:28,965
Now you're going
to get it.

832
00:33:29,049 --> 00:33:30,217
You're going to get it
where Nellie wore the beads.

833
00:33:30,300 --> 00:33:31,426
No, Nick!

834
00:33:31,510 --> 00:33:33,303
Not here in front
of your parents!

835
00:33:33,386 --> 00:33:34,596
Oh, stop it!

836
00:33:34,679 --> 00:33:36,223
But you can draw
your own conclusions.

837
00:33:36,306 --> 00:33:37,474
[growling playfully]

838
00:33:39,142 --> 00:33:41,645
Nick: This will teach you
the power of the press.

839
00:33:41,728 --> 00:33:42,896
[laughing]

840
00:33:44,940 --> 00:33:47,150
A fine son
you brought up!

841
00:33:47,234 --> 00:33:49,027
A wife beater!

842
00:33:49,110 --> 00:33:50,487
A brave boy.

843
00:33:50,570 --> 00:33:51,696
I wanted
to do that

844
00:33:51,780 --> 00:33:52,781
to mother
for 40 years.

845
00:33:52,864 --> 00:33:54,199
I dare you.

846
00:33:54,282 --> 00:33:55,534
[doorbell buzzes]

847
00:33:55,617 --> 00:33:58,411
Who can that be?

848
00:33:58,495 --> 00:34:00,997
Well, one way
to find out.

849
00:34:04,709 --> 00:34:06,002
Are you
Mr. Nick Charles?

850
00:34:06,086 --> 00:34:07,629
Yes.

851
00:34:07,712 --> 00:34:09,339
I wonder if i could
talk to you for a few minutes.

852
00:34:09,422 --> 00:34:10,840
You see, there's something
i've got to get off my mind.

853
00:34:10,924 --> 00:34:12,300
Uh!

854
00:34:33,029 --> 00:34:34,364
He's dead, Nick.

855
00:34:34,447 --> 00:34:36,491
[Asta growling]

856
00:34:36,575 --> 00:34:38,785
[barking]

857
00:34:40,078 --> 00:34:41,288
Don't move him, dad.

858
00:34:47,794 --> 00:34:49,629
Man: Is that you, Nick?

859
00:34:49,713 --> 00:34:51,506
- Brogan?
Brogan: Yeah.

860
00:34:51,590 --> 00:34:54,384
- Where are you?
Brogan: Here in the bushes.

861
00:34:54,467 --> 00:34:56,511
- Did you hear a shot?
- No.

862
00:34:56,595 --> 00:34:57,679
That's funny.
Neither did i.

863
00:34:57,762 --> 00:34:59,014
Why? Something
happen?

864
00:34:59,097 --> 00:35:00,724
Nora: Nicky, what is it?

865
00:35:00,807 --> 00:35:03,935
Oh, darling, it's Mr. Brogan.
Do you remember?

866
00:35:04,019 --> 00:35:06,354
Nick: He was just coming
to call on us.

867
00:35:06,438 --> 00:35:07,731
What's he doing
in the bushes?

868
00:35:09,190 --> 00:35:10,942
Why, I... I... I...

869
00:35:11,026 --> 00:35:13,903
He was lighting
a cigarette.

870
00:35:13,987 --> 00:35:16,823
Will you come up
to the house with us?

871
00:35:16,906 --> 00:35:17,991
A man's
just been shot.

872
00:35:18,074 --> 00:35:19,367
Oh.

873
00:35:19,451 --> 00:35:20,577
Nick: The bell rang,

874
00:35:20,660 --> 00:35:22,912
I opened the door,
he keeled over.

875
00:35:22,996 --> 00:35:25,957
Oh, mother, dad, this is an old
friend of mine Mr. Brogan.

876
00:35:26,041 --> 00:35:27,292
How do you do,
Mrs. Charles?

877
00:35:27,375 --> 00:35:28,335
How do you do,
doctor?

878
00:35:28,418 --> 00:35:29,711
How do you
do, sir?

879
00:35:29,794 --> 00:35:32,172
Time and tide
wait for no man.

880
00:35:32,255 --> 00:35:33,548
Tsk tsk tsk tsk.

881
00:35:33,632 --> 00:35:35,842
Nick, you better phone
Bruce Clayworth.

882
00:35:35,925 --> 00:35:37,594
He's the official
coroner in this town.

883
00:35:37,677 --> 00:35:38,845
He lives
just down the street.

884
00:35:38,928 --> 00:35:39,929
Yes.
What's his number?

885
00:35:40,013 --> 00:35:41,514
148.

886
00:35:41,598 --> 00:35:43,725
You know, doctor,
this is just typical of Nick.

887
00:35:43,808 --> 00:35:45,685
Wherever he goes,
you always find bodies.

888
00:35:45,769 --> 00:35:47,896
It's just typical.

889
00:35:47,979 --> 00:35:49,481
Is Dr. Clayworth there?

890
00:35:49,564 --> 00:35:50,732
Just a moment.

891
00:35:52,984 --> 00:35:54,069
Dr. Clayworth?

892
00:35:54,152 --> 00:35:55,236
Man: Yes?

893
00:35:55,320 --> 00:35:56,655
Phone for you.

894
00:35:56,738 --> 00:35:57,864
Man: Alright.

895
00:35:59,824 --> 00:36:01,826
Thank you, Miss Harling.

896
00:36:05,080 --> 00:36:06,915
- Hello.
- Hello, Bruce.

897
00:36:06,998 --> 00:36:09,626
This is Nick Charles.

898
00:36:09,709 --> 00:36:11,628
A man's just been
shot over here.

899
00:36:11,711 --> 00:36:13,963
What?
Well, who is it?

900
00:36:14,047 --> 00:36:15,423
I don't know.

901
00:36:15,507 --> 00:36:16,549
Would you notify
the police?

902
00:36:16,633 --> 00:36:18,009
Sure, I will, Nick,

903
00:36:18,093 --> 00:36:20,095
and i'll come
right over, too.

904
00:36:21,888 --> 00:36:23,932
I'll be through here
in just a minute.

905
00:36:26,059 --> 00:36:28,978
Now, Nick, I don't want
to seem too personal,

906
00:36:29,062 --> 00:36:30,355
but if you're
going to tell me

907
00:36:30,438 --> 00:36:31,481
you don't know anything
about this thing,

908
00:36:31,564 --> 00:36:33,608
all i can say
is baloney.

909
00:36:33,692 --> 00:36:35,610
Mac, it happened
just as i said.

910
00:36:35,694 --> 00:36:37,237
The bell rang.
I went to the door.

911
00:36:37,320 --> 00:36:39,656
The boy started to say
something and was shot.

912
00:36:39,739 --> 00:36:41,616
- Did you ever see him before?
- No.

913
00:36:41,700 --> 00:36:43,118
The name's
Peter Berton.

914
00:36:43,201 --> 00:36:45,286
Yes, I know.
I know that, Dr. Charles.

915
00:36:45,370 --> 00:36:46,371
Well, I was
just telling you.

916
00:36:46,454 --> 00:36:47,414
He lives
at Tom's Auto Court.

917
00:36:47,497 --> 00:36:48,998
I know that, too.

918
00:36:49,082 --> 00:36:50,834
Just because you've gotten
used to me, Dr. Charles,

919
00:36:50,917 --> 00:36:52,460
doesn't mean
i haven't got any brain.

920
00:36:52,544 --> 00:36:54,421
I can handle more than
traffic problems, you know.

921
00:36:54,504 --> 00:36:56,881
Then handle it, and
let's get it over with.

922
00:36:56,965 --> 00:36:58,800
I'm not used to policemen
in my living room

923
00:36:58,883 --> 00:37:01,511
or people messing around
in my laboratory.

924
00:37:01,594 --> 00:37:02,887
I like peace and quiet.

925
00:37:02,971 --> 00:37:04,723
Brogan: Good for you,
Dr. Charles.

926
00:37:04,806 --> 00:37:07,350
Tennyson says,
"Peace shall pipe

927
00:37:07,434 --> 00:37:09,269
on her pastoral hill
a languid note

928
00:37:09,352 --> 00:37:10,854
and watch
her harvest ripen.”

929
00:37:10,937 --> 00:37:13,231
"Thanksgiving."

930
00:37:13,314 --> 00:37:14,858
MacGregor: Nick, did it
ever occur to you

931
00:37:14,941 --> 00:37:15,900
that somebody might
have been trying

932
00:37:15,984 --> 00:37:16,943
to take a potshot at you

933
00:37:17,026 --> 00:37:18,278
and hit
the boy instead?

934
00:37:18,361 --> 00:37:19,946
Well, that's
an angle.

935
00:37:20,029 --> 00:37:21,030
You know,
he might have taken

936
00:37:21,114 --> 00:37:22,282
a shot
at you and missed.

937
00:37:22,365 --> 00:37:25,160
And a miss
is as good as a mile.

938
00:37:25,243 --> 00:37:28,580
Mr. Brogan, if it isn't
too much trouble,

939
00:37:28,663 --> 00:37:30,999
would you mind telling
me where you came from?

940
00:37:31,082 --> 00:37:33,418
Why, I'm a friend
of Nick's. Get it?

941
00:37:33,501 --> 00:37:35,211
And i was just
passing by. Get it?

942
00:37:35,295 --> 00:37:36,629
So i thought
i'd just stop in.

943
00:37:36,713 --> 00:37:38,131
Nora: Get it?

944
00:37:38,214 --> 00:37:40,008
Do you usually
drop in the bushes?

945
00:37:40,091 --> 00:37:43,178
Well, can't a fella stop
to light a cigarette?

946
00:37:43,261 --> 00:37:44,554
If Mr. Charles can be

947
00:37:44,637 --> 00:37:46,014
of any help to you,
Mr. MacGregor,

948
00:37:46,097 --> 00:37:48,141
I'm sure he'd be
only too glad.

949
00:37:48,224 --> 00:37:50,769
<i>Oh, I'm
on a vacation.</i>

950
00:37:50,852 --> 00:37:53,021
Besides, you
can't just barge in

951
00:37:53,104 --> 00:37:54,314
<i>on another man's
case.</i>

952
00:37:54,397 --> 00:37:56,107
You could be called in
as a specialist.

953
00:37:56,191 --> 00:37:58,026
- Couldn't he, father?
- Well, I'm not so sure.

954
00:37:58,109 --> 00:37:59,903
Mother: Of course a man could be
called in as a specialist.

955
00:37:59,986 --> 00:38:01,279
You told me so yourself.

956
00:38:01,362 --> 00:38:03,114
Well, if i need any help,
I'll ask for it.

957
00:38:03,198 --> 00:38:04,991
That's
the right spirit.

958
00:38:05,074 --> 00:38:06,201
And the safety
of this community

959
00:38:06,284 --> 00:38:07,702
couldn't be
in better hands.

960
00:38:07,786 --> 00:38:09,162
Who'd like some cider?

961
00:38:09,245 --> 00:38:12,373
Nick? Oh, Nick.
Here's the bullet.

962
00:38:12,457 --> 00:38:13,750
I don't know much
about such things,

963
00:38:13,833 --> 00:38:15,543
but i imagine that
was fired from a .45

964
00:38:15,627 --> 00:38:17,045
or something
in that general field.

965
00:38:17,128 --> 00:38:18,713
Hmm... well,
give it to Mac.

966
00:38:18,797 --> 00:38:19,798
It's his show.

967
00:38:19,881 --> 00:38:21,257
Thanks.
I'll send this

968
00:38:21,341 --> 00:38:22,634
to a good
ballistics expert.

969
00:38:22,717 --> 00:38:25,595
Nora: Nick's a good
ballistics expert.

970
00:38:25,678 --> 00:38:28,681
I'm a ballistics expert
who's on a vacation.

971
00:38:28,765 --> 00:38:29,766
Who'll have cider?

972
00:38:29,849 --> 00:38:31,559
Very little water
in mine.

973
00:38:34,437 --> 00:38:36,231
Is the cider in here?

974
00:38:36,314 --> 00:38:37,732
Yes, sir.

975
00:38:40,568 --> 00:38:42,362
- Hilda.
- Yes, sir?

976
00:38:42,445 --> 00:38:45,031
How about
some glasses?

977
00:38:45,114 --> 00:38:47,116
Umm...

978
00:38:47,200 --> 00:38:49,035
- Hilda.
- Yes, sir?

979
00:38:49,118 --> 00:38:50,286
Suppose you do
the honors.

980
00:38:50,370 --> 00:38:51,955
Yes, sir.

981
00:39:03,174 --> 00:39:05,385
Man: Oh, thank you, sir.
- Yes, sir.

982
00:39:17,981 --> 00:39:19,148
What's the idea?

983
00:39:19,232 --> 00:39:20,692
We ain't had
a vacancy in two months.

984
00:39:20,775 --> 00:39:21,901
You have now.

985
00:39:21,985 --> 00:39:23,611
Peter Berton's
just been shot.

986
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:25,321
Peter Berton's
been shot?!

987
00:39:25,405 --> 00:39:27,407
It's number 19
with a bath and shower.

988
00:39:27,490 --> 00:39:29,409
I want to ask you
a few questions about him.

989
00:39:29,492 --> 00:39:31,452
Know nothing
about him.

990
00:39:31,536 --> 00:39:32,537
The less you notice
in this business,

991
00:39:32,620 --> 00:39:33,663
the better it is.

992
00:39:33,746 --> 00:39:35,832
Mum's the word
around here.

993
00:39:37,083 --> 00:39:38,501
Mum's the word.

994
00:39:40,670 --> 00:39:41,713
[door closes]

995
00:39:41,796 --> 00:39:42,964
Well, I always said

996
00:39:43,047 --> 00:39:44,883
something would
happen to that boy.

997
00:39:44,966 --> 00:39:46,217
Yes? Why?

998
00:39:46,301 --> 00:39:47,510
Bad-tempered and ornery.

999
00:39:47,594 --> 00:39:49,387
He had a fight
the other night.

1000
00:39:49,470 --> 00:39:51,055
A fight, huh?
With whom?

1001
00:39:51,139 --> 00:39:52,432
Don't know the name.
The other fella ended up

1002
00:39:52,515 --> 00:39:54,601
with two black eyes,
like a raccoon.

1003
00:39:54,684 --> 00:39:55,852
What was
the fight about?

1004
00:39:55,935 --> 00:39:57,562
Can't say for sure,
but like as not,

1005
00:39:57,645 --> 00:39:59,230
it was over
that Laurabel Ronson.

1006
00:39:59,314 --> 00:40:01,524
She was traipsing
over here all the time.

1007
00:40:01,608 --> 00:40:02,775
[door opens]

1008
00:40:04,569 --> 00:40:06,362
I said
mum's the word.

1009
00:40:06,446 --> 00:40:07,780
Mum's what word?

1010
00:40:07,864 --> 00:40:09,032
[telephone rings]

1011
00:40:11,451 --> 00:40:12,619
Yep.

1012
00:40:13,870 --> 00:40:15,121
Yep.

1013
00:40:15,204 --> 00:40:16,664
Nope.

1014
00:40:16,748 --> 00:40:18,291
- Was that MacGregor?
- Yep.

1015
00:40:18,374 --> 00:40:20,627
- Is he on his way?
- Yep.

1016
00:40:20,710 --> 00:40:22,587
Okay, because
when he comes,

1017
00:40:22,670 --> 00:40:25,048
- I'll be in number 19.
- Oh.

1018
00:40:25,131 --> 00:40:27,967
I hope you haven't
touched anything in there.

1019
00:40:28,051 --> 00:40:29,218
Nope.

1020
00:40:29,302 --> 00:40:32,805
We clean once a day
in the morning.

1021
00:40:32,889 --> 00:40:34,223
You two had better
stay here.

1022
00:40:34,307 --> 00:40:35,475
Woman: Yes, sir.

1023
00:40:35,558 --> 00:40:38,144
And remember,
mum's the word.

1024
00:40:38,227 --> 00:40:39,270
[door closes]

1025
00:40:45,443 --> 00:40:48,363
[dramatic music]

1026
00:41:10,009 --> 00:41:12,929
[dramatic music]

1027
00:41:56,597 --> 00:41:58,349
Nick: "Cubana Perfecto.”

1028
00:42:04,272 --> 00:42:07,191
[intense music]

1029
00:42:14,782 --> 00:42:16,451
Nick: "Boston Children's Home."

1030
00:42:17,243 --> 00:42:18,578
Hmm...

1031
00:42:24,959 --> 00:42:27,879
[intense music]

1032
00:42:28,838 --> 00:42:29,881
[thudding]

1033
00:42:29,964 --> 00:42:31,132
[clanging]

1034
00:42:36,596 --> 00:42:38,222
[winding clock]

1035
00:42:44,145 --> 00:42:45,772
Why don't you girls
go to bed?

1036
00:42:45,855 --> 00:42:47,023
I'm worried, Bertram.

1037
00:42:47,106 --> 00:42:48,608
Something might have
happened to him.

1038
00:42:48,691 --> 00:42:50,818
Nonsense. Nick's old enough
to take care of himself.

1039
00:42:50,902 --> 00:42:52,612
To think that i fell
for that cider routine.

1040
00:42:52,695 --> 00:42:55,198
He's probably got the case
half solved by now.

1041
00:42:55,281 --> 00:42:56,824
But where can he be?

1042
00:42:56,908 --> 00:42:58,993
He's probably turning
that auto camp upside-down.

1043
00:42:59,077 --> 00:43:00,411
Don't you think
it's possible

1044
00:43:00,495 --> 00:43:02,080
he might be turning
a drink upside-down?

1045
00:43:02,163 --> 00:43:03,790
Not on your tin time.

1046
00:43:03,873 --> 00:43:05,583
When Nick puts
his mind on a thing,

1047
00:43:05,666 --> 00:43:07,752
he never makes a false step.

1048
00:43:07,835 --> 00:43:09,879
[crash]

1049
00:43:17,386 --> 00:43:18,888
That's my boy.

1050
00:43:25,895 --> 00:43:27,939
Well, let's see,
Asta.

1051
00:43:28,022 --> 00:43:30,233
Where shall we put it?

1052
00:43:30,316 --> 00:43:33,486
I really shouldn't give him
a birthday present at all,

1053
00:43:33,569 --> 00:43:36,572
<i>sneaking off like that
and getting drunk...</i>

1054
00:43:36,656 --> 00:43:38,825
without me.

1055
00:43:38,908 --> 00:43:41,869
Hmm... running into
an old sweetheart.

1056
00:43:41,953 --> 00:43:45,665
If all his old sweethearts
were laid end to end,

1057
00:43:45,748 --> 00:43:47,792
I could use them
as a sidewalk.

1058
00:43:53,381 --> 00:43:55,675
[sniffing]

1059
00:43:55,758 --> 00:43:59,303
But he's
a pretty good guy.

1060
00:43:59,387 --> 00:44:01,764
He keeps us
in dog biscuits.

1061
00:44:03,516 --> 00:44:05,476
I hope he likes it.

1062
00:44:07,436 --> 00:44:13,317
"Ah. Nora, darling,
what a lovely surprise.”

1063
00:44:14,694 --> 00:44:15,945
Nick: Darling,

1064
00:44:16,028 --> 00:44:17,822
what time is it?

1065
00:44:17,905 --> 00:44:20,158
Uh, it's almost 11:00.

1066
00:44:20,241 --> 00:44:21,284
Whoo!

1067
00:44:23,578 --> 00:44:25,788
Oh, boy,
I am late.

1068
00:44:25,872 --> 00:44:28,166
♪ I've got a date ♪

1069
00:44:28,249 --> 00:44:29,542
[Kissing]

1070
00:44:29,625 --> 00:44:32,461
♪ Deep in the heart of Texas ♪

1071
00:44:32,545 --> 00:44:34,505
♪ Choose a tie ♪

1072
00:44:34,589 --> 00:44:36,591
♪ Then i must fly ♪

1073
00:44:36,674 --> 00:44:38,342
[Kissing]

1074
00:44:38,426 --> 00:44:40,511
♪ Deep in the heart of Texas ♪

1075
00:44:40,595 --> 00:44:41,888
[Nick continues singing]

1076
00:44:49,353 --> 00:44:52,940
Darling, where's my belt
with the gold buckle?

1077
00:44:53,024 --> 00:44:54,942
Buckle, buckle.
Who's got the buckle?

1078
00:44:55,026 --> 00:44:56,485
♪ Buckle down,
winsockie ♪

1079
00:44:56,569 --> 00:44:58,321
♪ Buckle down,
down, down ♪

1080
00:44:58,404 --> 00:45:00,156
There it is,
right in front of you.

1081
00:45:00,239 --> 00:45:01,324
Hmm?

1082
00:45:01,407 --> 00:45:04,827
[chuckles]

1083
00:45:04,911 --> 00:45:06,078
[Kissing]

1084
00:45:06,162 --> 00:45:10,082
♪ Deep in the heart of Texas ♪

1085
00:45:10,166 --> 00:45:11,584
Some detective.

1086
00:45:11,667 --> 00:45:14,086
<i>♪ Deep in the heart
of Texas ♪</i>

1087
00:45:15,588 --> 00:45:16,756
[Nick continues singing]

1088
00:45:26,599 --> 00:45:28,100
♪ Good-bye, mama ♪

1089
00:45:28,184 --> 00:45:29,268
<i>♪ I'm off to Yokohama ♪</i>

1090
00:45:29,352 --> 00:45:30,311
[Kissing]

1091
00:45:30,394 --> 00:45:31,854
♪ Deep in the heart... ♪

1092
00:45:31,938 --> 00:45:35,650
Nicky, what is this sudden
epidemic of kisses for?

1093
00:45:35,733 --> 00:45:38,152
For my birthday.
Remember?

1094
00:45:38,236 --> 00:45:39,403
[laughing]

1095
00:45:41,697 --> 00:45:44,033
♪ Deep in the heart of... ♪

1096
00:45:44,116 --> 00:45:45,451
Uh-oh.

1097
00:45:45,534 --> 00:45:47,036
You know what that is?

1098
00:45:47,119 --> 00:45:48,412
Remember that old mill
i pointed out to you

1099
00:45:48,496 --> 00:45:50,581
from the baggage car?
Well, that's it.

1100
00:45:50,665 --> 00:45:53,751
Ooh, what a pain in the neck
that turned out to be.

1101
00:45:53,834 --> 00:45:57,213
Full of snakes, skunks,
poison ivy,

1102
00:45:57,296 --> 00:45:58,923
and a truant officer.

1103
00:45:59,006 --> 00:46:00,967
Gives me the shudders
just to look at it.

1104
00:46:01,050 --> 00:46:02,927
[Nick singing]

1105
00:46:07,723 --> 00:46:09,850
Hilda, take this out
and burn it.

1106
00:46:09,934 --> 00:46:12,436
- Don't you like it?
- No.

1107
00:46:12,520 --> 00:46:14,146
Can't say i blame you.

1108
00:46:14,230 --> 00:46:17,233
Why, Hilda, what are you
doing with that picture?

1109
00:46:17,316 --> 00:46:19,777
Mrs. Charles
told me to burn it.

1110
00:46:19,860 --> 00:46:22,613
Oh, let me see.

1111
00:46:22,697 --> 00:46:24,865
Why, I think
it's very pretty.

1112
00:46:24,949 --> 00:46:26,158
It's just
the thing to give

1113
00:46:26,242 --> 00:46:27,576
to the bazaar
at the hotel.

1114
00:46:28,536 --> 00:46:29,996
It's alright with me.

1115
00:46:31,497 --> 00:46:34,166
I'll tell miss Laurabel
you're here.

1116
00:46:34,250 --> 00:46:35,376
Thank you.

1117
00:46:38,713 --> 00:46:39,964
Maid: Miss Laurabel.

1118
00:46:41,966 --> 00:46:43,217
Miss Laurabel.

1119
00:46:59,567 --> 00:47:01,360
I hope i'm not
disturbing you, Miss Ronson.

1120
00:47:01,444 --> 00:47:03,112
No. It's alright.

1121
00:47:03,195 --> 00:47:05,448
You came to talk to me
about Peter Berton, didn't you?

1122
00:47:05,531 --> 00:47:08,200
Yes. And you're
very brave to see me

1123
00:47:08,284 --> 00:47:09,327
at a time like this.

1124
00:47:09,410 --> 00:47:11,287
Oh, it doesn't matter.

1125
00:47:11,370 --> 00:47:13,789
People are born.
People die.

1126
00:47:13,873 --> 00:47:16,417
Life goes on.

1127
00:47:16,500 --> 00:47:18,044
Poor Peter.

1128
00:47:18,127 --> 00:47:20,671
"At least he's outsoared
the shadow of our night.

1129
00:47:20,755 --> 00:47:23,841
Envy, pain, and hate
can touch him not."

1130
00:47:23,924 --> 00:47:24,967
That's Shelley.

1131
00:47:25,051 --> 00:47:26,260
I always turn
to the poets

1132
00:47:26,344 --> 00:47:28,888
for comfort
in all my sorrow.

1133
00:47:28,971 --> 00:47:30,514
Yeah. Me, too.

1134
00:47:30,598 --> 00:47:32,350
Now, about Peter...

1135
00:47:32,433 --> 00:47:34,143
I just wanted to ask
you a few things

1136
00:47:34,226 --> 00:47:36,896
about his friends,
his family.

1137
00:47:36,979 --> 00:47:40,316
He was alone.
He had only me.

1138
00:47:41,233 --> 00:47:43,027
Oh. Well, uh...

1139
00:47:43,110 --> 00:47:45,404
he must have talked
about his family, though,

1140
00:47:45,488 --> 00:47:46,614
his childhood.

1141
00:47:46,697 --> 00:47:48,366
He talked of nothing.

1142
00:47:48,449 --> 00:47:50,618
Our souls
and spirits communed.

1143
00:47:50,701 --> 00:47:53,579
Words would have been
empty, meaningless.

1144
00:47:53,662 --> 00:47:55,623
Yes, I can
understand that.

1145
00:47:55,706 --> 00:47:57,124
Cigarette,
Mr. Charles?

1146
00:47:57,208 --> 00:47:58,459
Oh, thank you,
no.

1147
00:47:58,542 --> 00:47:59,752
A cigar?

1148
00:47:59,835 --> 00:48:01,629
I rather lost interest
in cigars.

1149
00:48:01,712 --> 00:48:03,089
Oh, father has
some very good ones...

1150
00:48:03,172 --> 00:48:05,257
a special brand he
keeps all for himself.

1151
00:48:05,341 --> 00:48:06,801
Oh, a special brand.

1152
00:48:06,884 --> 00:48:08,427
Yes. Won't you
try one?

1153
00:48:08,511 --> 00:48:10,888
Nick: "Cubana perfecto.” Hmm...

1154
00:48:12,098 --> 00:48:13,265
Well, yes, yes.

1155
00:48:13,349 --> 00:48:15,226
This does
interest me.

1156
00:48:15,309 --> 00:48:16,352
[sniffs]

1157
00:48:16,435 --> 00:48:17,978
Thank you.

1158
00:48:18,062 --> 00:48:19,980
You and Peter saw
quite a good deal

1159
00:48:20,064 --> 00:48:21,190
of each other, huh?

1160
00:48:21,273 --> 00:48:23,442
Yes. Fellow
artists, you know.

1161
00:48:23,526 --> 00:48:25,653
That fight he got into
recently must have been

1162
00:48:25,736 --> 00:48:27,321
rather distressing
to you, wasn't it?

1163
00:48:27,405 --> 00:48:28,823
- Fight?
- Yes.

1164
00:48:28,906 --> 00:48:31,117
He gave somebody
a pair of black eyes.

1165
00:48:31,200 --> 00:48:33,244
I know absolutely
nothing about that.

1166
00:48:33,327 --> 00:48:34,829
Is that so? Hmm...

1167
00:48:34,912 --> 00:48:37,873
Your father didn't
approve of Peter, did he?

1168
00:48:37,957 --> 00:48:38,999
Poor dad.

1169
00:48:39,083 --> 00:48:40,376
So provincial,
you know.

1170
00:48:40,459 --> 00:48:42,294
He just didn't
understand.

1171
00:48:42,378 --> 00:48:45,297
Oh, I tried again and again
to explain to him

1172
00:48:45,381 --> 00:48:48,217
how platonic
and beautiful it was,

1173
00:48:48,300 --> 00:48:49,718
but he just
made scenes.

1174
00:48:49,802 --> 00:48:51,137
I thought
he was going to have

1175
00:48:51,220 --> 00:48:53,180
a stroke or something.
Oh, it was awful.

1176
00:48:53,264 --> 00:48:54,348
Nick: You poor child.

1177
00:48:54,432 --> 00:48:56,100
Oh, and it wasn't
only dad.

1178
00:48:56,183 --> 00:48:59,520
No one understood what Peter
and i meant to each other.

1179
00:48:59,603 --> 00:49:02,690
Why, Tom Clayworth made
such a fuss if i even...

1180
00:49:02,773 --> 00:49:04,984
Oh, well, you wouldn't
be interested in all that.

1181
00:49:05,067 --> 00:49:07,862
On the contrary.
What about Tom?

1182
00:49:07,945 --> 00:49:09,905
Well, you know
what an emotional type Tom is,

1183
00:49:09,989 --> 00:49:11,449
and so jealous.

1184
00:49:11,532 --> 00:49:12,950
Why, if he heard
i even spoke to Peter,

1185
00:49:13,033 --> 00:49:14,368
he'd hit
the ceiling.

1186
00:49:14,452 --> 00:49:15,703
Did he ever
hit Peter?

1187
00:49:15,786 --> 00:49:17,204
Oh, no.

1188
00:49:17,288 --> 00:49:18,497
Were you afraid
he might?

1189
00:49:18,581 --> 00:49:21,917
Well, you see...
Oh, Mr. Charles.

1190
00:49:22,001 --> 00:49:23,502
Tom had nothing to do
with Peter's death.

1191
00:49:23,586 --> 00:49:25,171
I know that.

1192
00:49:25,254 --> 00:49:28,215
Mm-hmm. But the last time
you went out to see Peter,

1193
00:49:28,299 --> 00:49:31,177
wasn't it to warn him
that Tom was jealous,

1194
00:49:31,260 --> 00:49:33,804
perhaps made threats?

1195
00:49:33,888 --> 00:49:36,515
You're quite wrong,
Mr. Charles.

1196
00:49:36,599 --> 00:49:38,642
Was it to warn him
against your father?

1197
00:49:40,644 --> 00:49:42,062
My father?

1198
00:49:42,146 --> 00:49:43,939
Yes. He didn't want
you to see Peter.

1199
00:49:44,023 --> 00:49:45,858
He made violent
scenes about it.

1200
00:49:45,941 --> 00:49:47,610
You told me so.

1201
00:49:49,987 --> 00:49:53,282
You... you tricked me
into telling you that.

1202
00:49:53,365 --> 00:49:55,034
Tricked you?

1203
00:49:55,117 --> 00:49:56,285
Say, what do you think
this is, Miss Ronson,

1204
00:49:56,368 --> 00:49:58,078
a parlor game?

1205
00:49:58,162 --> 00:50:00,206
A man has been
murdered.

1206
00:50:00,289 --> 00:50:01,707
Your father threatened
Peter, didn't he?

1207
00:50:01,790 --> 00:50:02,958
No, that isn't true.

1208
00:50:03,042 --> 00:50:04,418
You must believe me!
I swear it!

1209
00:50:04,502 --> 00:50:06,545
- I believe you.
- No, you don't.

1210
00:50:06,629 --> 00:50:07,963
You're just trying to trick me
into telling you more.

1211
00:50:08,047 --> 00:50:09,340
Well, I won't!

1212
00:50:09,423 --> 00:50:10,883
And i won't listen
to your accusations!

1213
00:50:10,966 --> 00:50:13,427
Get out!
Go on! Get out!

1214
00:50:13,511 --> 00:50:14,803
Oh!

1215
00:50:28,275 --> 00:50:30,819
I'm sorry if i upset her,
Mr. Ronson.

1216
00:50:30,903 --> 00:50:32,696
What do you
want here?

1217
00:50:32,780 --> 00:50:35,282
I wanted to talk to Laurabel
about Peter Berton.

1218
00:50:35,366 --> 00:50:36,992
What about
Peter Berton?

1219
00:50:37,076 --> 00:50:39,078
Well, for one thing,
he's dead.

1220
00:50:39,161 --> 00:50:41,247
And you think
my daughter killed him?

1221
00:50:41,330 --> 00:50:43,457
Well, no, but, uh...

1222
00:50:43,541 --> 00:50:45,709
I wanted to ask her
a few things about him...

1223
00:50:45,793 --> 00:50:48,963
who his friends were
and who his enemies were.

1224
00:50:50,756 --> 00:50:53,551
Why did you object to him seeing
your daughter, Mr. Ronson?

1225
00:50:53,634 --> 00:50:56,387
- Who says i objected?
- Your daughter.

1226
00:50:56,470 --> 00:50:58,764
I'm not responsible
for what Laurabel says.

1227
00:50:58,847 --> 00:51:01,767
She's a girl with a very
vivid imagination.

1228
00:51:01,850 --> 00:51:03,852
Why should i
object to him?

1229
00:51:03,936 --> 00:51:06,772
That's what i
would like to know.

1230
00:51:06,855 --> 00:51:08,941
Now, look here, Charles.
I'm just as interested

1231
00:51:09,024 --> 00:51:10,651
in seeing justice
done as you are,

1232
00:51:10,734 --> 00:51:12,653
but i think you
ought to be careful.

1233
00:51:12,736 --> 00:51:15,072
I know that you don't want
to hurt innocent people.

1234
00:51:15,155 --> 00:51:17,575
You don't want to damage
good reputations needlessly.

1235
00:51:17,658 --> 00:51:20,119
That might be harmful
to the whole community.

1236
00:51:20,202 --> 00:51:22,162
Your own family,
your own father

1237
00:51:22,246 --> 00:51:23,872
might have
ambitions and plans

1238
00:51:23,956 --> 00:51:26,041
that could be ruined.

1239
00:51:26,125 --> 00:51:28,210
You mean my father's
ambition for a hospital

1240
00:51:28,294 --> 00:51:30,796
might be blocked?

1241
00:51:30,879 --> 00:51:32,673
Just think
that over, Charles.

1242
00:51:34,341 --> 00:51:36,135
Yes.

1243
00:51:36,218 --> 00:51:37,511
I will think it over,
Mr. Ronson.

1244
00:51:37,595 --> 00:51:39,179
I will, indeed.

1245
00:51:39,263 --> 00:51:41,181
And i'll also
think over

1246
00:51:41,265 --> 00:51:43,183
what you were doing
in Peter Berton's cabin

1247
00:51:43,267 --> 00:51:46,020
the day he was killed.
Good day.

1248
00:51:46,103 --> 00:51:47,271
[door closes]

1249
00:51:48,772 --> 00:51:50,858
Well, how are you, Mac?
Right on the job, I see.

1250
00:51:50,941 --> 00:51:53,277
Say, that was a dirty trick,
changing those numbers.

1251
00:51:53,360 --> 00:51:54,653
I didn't find out i
was in the wrong cabin

1252
00:51:54,737 --> 00:51:56,071
till this morning.

1253
00:51:56,155 --> 00:51:57,364
That was just
the Halloween in me.

1254
00:51:57,448 --> 00:51:59,116
Well, this
isn't Halloween.

1255
00:51:59,199 --> 00:52:01,827
Say, I thought you
were on a vacation.

1256
00:52:01,910 --> 00:52:03,912
Oh, I just thought
i'd help a bit.

1257
00:52:03,996 --> 00:52:06,332
Well, you didn't happen to
run into anything, did you?

1258
00:52:06,415 --> 00:52:08,459
Are you keeping
an eye on Crazy Mary?

1259
00:52:08,542 --> 00:52:10,628
Why Crazy Mary?

1260
00:52:10,711 --> 00:52:12,463
Well, as i remember,
she used to go

1261
00:52:12,546 --> 00:52:14,340
on the warpath
at times, didn't she?

1262
00:52:14,423 --> 00:52:15,799
Say, how does anybody

1263
00:52:15,883 --> 00:52:17,301
ever get into her shack
to talk with her?

1264
00:52:17,384 --> 00:52:19,303
Nobody ever does,
except Doc Clayworth.

1265
00:52:19,386 --> 00:52:20,679
Last time
i was out there,

1266
00:52:20,763 --> 00:52:22,097
I got conked in the head
with a coffeepot.

1267
00:52:22,181 --> 00:52:25,017
- No?
- Say, talking of the devil.

1268
00:52:25,100 --> 00:52:26,435
Bruce: Hello, Nick.
- Hiya, Bruce.

1269
00:52:26,518 --> 00:52:27,978
- Hello, Mac.
- How are you, doc?

1270
00:52:28,062 --> 00:52:29,813
I was just telling Nick
you're about the only one

1271
00:52:29,897 --> 00:52:31,398
could get him in
to talk to Crazy Mary.

1272
00:52:31,482 --> 00:52:32,691
Oh, sure.
Anytime, Nick.

1273
00:52:32,775 --> 00:52:35,152
Thanks. How did
the autopsy come out?

1274
00:52:35,235 --> 00:52:37,696
<i>We found that that bullet
entered the boy's back</i>

1275
00:52:37,780 --> 00:52:39,448
through the large
rhomboid on the left

1276
00:52:39,531 --> 00:52:40,866
and was stopped

1277
00:52:40,949 --> 00:52:43,452
by his sternocostal
joint on the right.

1278
00:52:43,535 --> 00:52:45,579
Hmm...

1279
00:52:45,663 --> 00:52:46,789
That tells us a lot,
doesn't it?

1280
00:52:46,872 --> 00:52:48,540
Yeah. Does it?

1281
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:52,044
Well, Mac, keep pitching.

1282
00:52:52,127 --> 00:52:54,463
Bad ones. Always gave me
his bad pictures to sell,

1283
00:52:54,546 --> 00:52:56,006
never his good ones.

1284
00:52:56,090 --> 00:52:59,176
Just...higgledy-piggledy,
that's what he was, yes.

1285
00:52:59,259 --> 00:53:01,220
You know, artists
are all like that.

1286
00:53:01,303 --> 00:53:04,264
They keep their good pictures
and sell their bad ones.

1287
00:53:04,348 --> 00:53:06,058
It seems a good artist

1288
00:53:06,141 --> 00:53:09,728
is just naturally...
higgledy-piggledy.

1289
00:53:09,812 --> 00:53:12,106
Maybe that's why
he's a good artist.

1290
00:53:13,357 --> 00:53:16,193
Or maybe it's reversed.

1291
00:53:16,276 --> 00:53:19,279
How much did you usually
get for his paintings?

1292
00:53:19,363 --> 00:53:20,739
Whose paintings?

1293
00:53:20,823 --> 00:53:23,283
Well, the boy we're
talking about...

1294
00:53:23,367 --> 00:53:24,618
higgledy-piggledy.

1295
00:53:24,702 --> 00:53:28,288
Oh, yes. That one.
$50 a picture.

1296
00:53:28,372 --> 00:53:30,082
Could you have gotten
more for his better ones?

1297
00:53:30,165 --> 00:53:32,042
Oh, gracious me, yes.

1298
00:53:32,126 --> 00:53:33,961
Twice as much.
Three times.

1299
00:53:34,044 --> 00:53:36,088
I guess the boy
was loaded, huh?

1300
00:53:36,171 --> 00:53:37,339
He was what?

1301
00:53:37,423 --> 00:53:39,591
He had no economic
problems, hmm?

1302
00:53:41,301 --> 00:53:43,470
Or else maybe he was
just, you know...

1303
00:53:43,554 --> 00:53:44,722
Uh...

1304
00:53:44,805 --> 00:53:45,848
Yes.

1305
00:53:45,931 --> 00:53:47,224
Higgledy-piggledy,
huh?

1306
00:53:47,307 --> 00:53:49,059
Yes, I'm sure
he must have been.

1307
00:53:49,143 --> 00:53:51,270
Well, thank you
very much.

1308
00:53:51,353 --> 00:53:52,730
Good-bye now.

1309
00:53:52,813 --> 00:53:54,982
Beg your pardon?

1310
00:53:55,065 --> 00:53:56,650
I said
good-bye now.

1311
00:53:56,734 --> 00:53:58,694
"Good-bye now?"

1312
00:53:58,777 --> 00:54:00,612
There's no sense to that.

1313
00:54:00,696 --> 00:54:01,947
Obviously it's now.

1314
00:54:02,030 --> 00:54:03,532
I mean,
you wouldn't say,

1315
00:54:03,615 --> 00:54:07,870
"Good-bye tomorrow"
or "Good-bye two hours ago."

1316
00:54:07,953 --> 00:54:10,414
You've got hold of
something there, brother.

1317
00:54:10,497 --> 00:54:12,541
I've got hold
of something...

1318
00:54:12,624 --> 00:54:14,209
I haven't got
hold of anything.

1319
00:54:14,293 --> 00:54:16,920
And i'm not your brother!

1320
00:54:17,004 --> 00:54:18,338
If he's here
on official business,

1321
00:54:18,422 --> 00:54:20,174
why doesn't he let
somebody know about it?

1322
00:54:20,257 --> 00:54:21,592
Why the mystery?

1323
00:54:21,675 --> 00:54:22,968
Besides, we have
a perfectly good

1324
00:54:23,051 --> 00:54:24,678
police department
of our own.

1325
00:54:24,762 --> 00:54:27,639
Well, what do you
want me to do?

1326
00:54:27,723 --> 00:54:30,017
I just want to give you
a word of advice.

1327
00:54:30,100 --> 00:54:31,351
I have reason
to believe

1328
00:54:31,435 --> 00:54:33,395
that Mr. Ronson is
not at all pleased

1329
00:54:33,479 --> 00:54:35,314
with his interfering
in people's lives.

1330
00:54:35,397 --> 00:54:37,191
It's upsetting
the town.

1331
00:54:37,274 --> 00:54:39,943
It might be better
if you asked him to leave.

1332
00:54:40,027 --> 00:54:42,863
Leave?
But he's my son.

1333
00:54:42,946 --> 00:54:44,072
He's just
a meddling fool.

1334
00:54:44,156 --> 00:54:45,616
That's what he is.

1335
00:54:45,699 --> 00:54:47,034
Did Ronson say that?

1336
00:54:47,117 --> 00:54:49,787
No, no, no.
That's my opinion.

1337
00:54:49,870 --> 00:54:51,914
Have you talked
with Ronson about this?

1338
00:54:51,997 --> 00:54:53,665
No, but i have
reason to believe...

1339
00:54:53,749 --> 00:54:56,043
What you believe
doesn't interest me.

1340
00:54:56,126 --> 00:54:58,462
I think
i'll be leaving.

1341
00:54:58,545 --> 00:55:00,464
I think you're making
a great mistake, doctor.

1342
00:55:00,547 --> 00:55:01,924
You've been working on

1343
00:55:02,007 --> 00:55:04,343
that hospital project
of yours for years.

1344
00:55:04,426 --> 00:55:05,636
I know your heart's
set on it,

1345
00:55:05,719 --> 00:55:08,263
and it's practically
a reality now.

1346
00:55:08,347 --> 00:55:09,515
It would be a shame

1347
00:55:09,598 --> 00:55:12,601
if, at the last minute,
it fell through.

1348
00:55:12,684 --> 00:55:15,562
Tatum, I think
you're a stinker.

1349
00:55:17,439 --> 00:55:19,608
[crying]

1350
00:55:19,691 --> 00:55:23,987
I think Tatum is a two-timing,
double-crossing rat.

1351
00:55:24,071 --> 00:55:25,489
Now, now, now,
mother. Mother.

1352
00:55:25,572 --> 00:55:27,491
We mustn't spoil
Nick's birthday.

1353
00:55:27,574 --> 00:55:29,368
Now, you must smile.
Now, smile.

1354
00:55:29,451 --> 00:55:32,120
No, no, no.
Nice, pretty smile.

1355
00:55:32,204 --> 00:55:33,956
That's right.

1356
00:55:40,170 --> 00:55:43,048
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

1357
00:55:43,131 --> 00:55:45,884
<i>♪ Happy birthday to you ♪</i>

1358
00:55:45,968 --> 00:55:48,554
♪ Happy birthday,
dear Nicky ♪

1359
00:55:48,637 --> 00:55:50,597
<i>♪ We're glad to see you ♪</i>

1360
00:55:50,681 --> 00:55:53,559
Oh! That's
beautiful, ma.

1361
00:55:53,642 --> 00:55:55,227
Thanks, dad.

1362
00:55:55,310 --> 00:55:57,020
Oh, that's
lovely, mother.

1363
00:55:57,104 --> 00:55:58,480
One, two, three, four...

1364
00:55:58,564 --> 00:56:00,691
Ah. Don't be a cad.

1365
00:56:00,774 --> 00:56:01,984
Why, this
makes me feel

1366
00:56:02,067 --> 00:56:03,318
as if i were
in short pants again.

1367
00:56:03,402 --> 00:56:04,570
That i want to see.

1368
00:56:04,653 --> 00:56:06,321
[chuckles]

1369
00:56:06,405 --> 00:56:07,364
Here goes.

1370
00:56:07,447 --> 00:56:08,699
Oh, make a wish.

1371
00:56:08,782 --> 00:56:11,743
Oh, yes. Alright.

1372
00:56:11,827 --> 00:56:13,829
Here's luck
to dad's hospital.

1373
00:56:13,912 --> 00:56:14,997
You shouldn't
tell your wish.

1374
00:56:15,080 --> 00:56:16,206
It may not
come true.

1375
00:56:16,290 --> 00:56:18,709
Well, this one will.

1376
00:56:18,792 --> 00:56:20,752
Hang onto your hats.

1377
00:56:20,836 --> 00:56:22,379
[Hilda screaming]

1378
00:56:26,717 --> 00:56:28,886
A man!
There was a man!

1379
00:56:28,969 --> 00:56:30,220
- Where?
- In your room!

1380
00:56:30,304 --> 00:56:31,471
Who was it,
Hilda?

1381
00:56:31,555 --> 00:56:32,931
Hilda: It was dark!
I couldn't see!

1382
00:56:33,015 --> 00:56:34,850
I walked in,
and there he was!

1383
00:56:52,242 --> 00:56:53,619
Oh...

1384
00:56:53,702 --> 00:56:54,912
Oh!

1385
00:56:54,995 --> 00:56:56,079
[crash]

1386
00:56:56,163 --> 00:56:57,414
[screaming]

1387
00:57:02,794 --> 00:57:04,296
What happened?

1388
00:57:04,379 --> 00:57:07,090
It was the table you fixed.
It's fainted again.

1389
00:57:13,847 --> 00:57:15,933
[Asta barking]

1390
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:35,118
Come out of there.

1391
00:57:36,912 --> 00:57:37,955
It's me, Nick.

1392
00:57:38,038 --> 00:57:38,997
For the love of...

1393
00:57:39,081 --> 00:57:40,582
Did you see anyone?

1394
00:57:40,666 --> 00:57:42,209
No. I just stepped
into the bushes for a minute.

1395
00:57:42,292 --> 00:57:45,003
- Why, Brogan...
- Why? What's up?

1396
00:57:45,087 --> 00:57:46,546
Somebody's been
casing my room.

1397
00:57:46,630 --> 00:57:47,798
Gee, I must
have missed him.

1398
00:57:47,881 --> 00:57:48,882
You certainly did.

1399
00:57:48,966 --> 00:57:50,092
I'm sorry, Nick,

1400
00:57:50,175 --> 00:57:51,259
but i got the dope
from Boston.

1401
00:57:51,343 --> 00:57:52,469
You were right
about the kid.

1402
00:57:52,552 --> 00:57:53,929
I got it all
written out here.

1403
00:57:54,012 --> 00:57:55,180
Nora: Nick.

1404
00:57:55,263 --> 00:57:56,765
Nick: Oh, it's
Mr. Brogan, dear.

1405
00:57:56,848 --> 00:57:59,393
I can let you have this lot
at a dollar a dozen.

1406
00:57:59,476 --> 00:58:00,602
Good evening,
Mrs. Charles.

1407
00:58:00,686 --> 00:58:02,854
Lighting
a cigarette again?

1408
00:58:02,938 --> 00:58:04,356
Well, no, no.
I was just going to

1409
00:58:04,439 --> 00:58:05,899
ask him to have
some cake with us.

1410
00:58:05,983 --> 00:58:07,317
Of course.
He can't stay

1411
00:58:07,401 --> 00:58:09,403
out here
in the bushes.

1412
00:58:12,239 --> 00:58:13,407
Well, there's tricks
to every trade,

1413
00:58:13,490 --> 00:58:14,825
as the saying goes.

1414
00:58:14,908 --> 00:58:16,326
I had
3,000 maternity cards

1415
00:58:16,410 --> 00:58:18,286
announcing the birth
of a baby girl.

1416
00:58:18,370 --> 00:58:20,747
All of a sudden,
everybody starts having boys.

1417
00:58:20,831 --> 00:58:22,624
Here i am,
stuck with a lot of cards.

1418
00:58:22,708 --> 00:58:24,960
It was practically impossible
to sell boys' cards

1419
00:58:25,043 --> 00:58:26,503
for girls' cards,
especially when the picture

1420
00:58:26,586 --> 00:58:28,005
was of a stork
wearing a high hat

1421
00:58:28,088 --> 00:58:29,881
with a diaper
in his mouth.

1422
00:58:29,965 --> 00:58:32,092
The diaper was what we call
a breakaway. Get it?

1423
00:58:32,175 --> 00:58:33,343
[laughing]

1424
00:58:35,512 --> 00:58:37,889
Nicky, how long have
you known Brogan?

1425
00:58:37,973 --> 00:58:39,307
Darling, did i tell you

1426
00:58:39,391 --> 00:58:41,268
how pretty you look
for my birthday dinner?

1427
00:58:41,351 --> 00:58:42,644
No, you didn't.

1428
00:58:42,728 --> 00:58:44,479
Nicky, has Brogan
got a police record?

1429
00:58:44,563 --> 00:58:45,814
Well, I meant
to tell you.

1430
00:58:45,897 --> 00:58:47,274
Honey, your hair
is tinged

1431
00:58:47,357 --> 00:58:49,818
with the russet shades
of beautiful autumn.

1432
00:58:49,901 --> 00:58:52,362
Look, you're holding
something back about Brogan.

1433
00:58:52,446 --> 00:58:53,989
He's a definite
criminal type.

1434
00:58:54,072 --> 00:58:56,324
I can tell by the shape
of his head.

1435
00:58:56,408 --> 00:58:58,452
Well, yes, there was
a little something

1436
00:58:58,535 --> 00:59:00,037
about an old lady who was
found in a trunk once.

1437
00:59:00,120 --> 00:59:01,079
Uh-huh!

1438
00:59:01,163 --> 00:59:02,831
And your ears are like

1439
00:59:02,914 --> 00:59:05,083
the twin petals
of a budding rose.

1440
00:59:05,167 --> 00:59:07,127
Later, darling.
Now, look.

1441
00:59:07,210 --> 00:59:08,545
I've got this
all figured out.

1442
00:59:08,628 --> 00:59:09,838
Brogan was in the bushes

1443
00:59:09,921 --> 00:59:10,881
the night the murder
was committed.

1444
00:59:10,964 --> 00:59:12,174
Check?

1445
00:59:12,257 --> 00:59:13,341
He was in the bushes
again tonight

1446
00:59:13,425 --> 00:59:14,426
when our room
was ransacked.

1447
00:59:14,509 --> 00:59:15,552
Double check.

1448
00:59:15,635 --> 00:59:17,304
Nicky, he's our man,

1449
00:59:17,387 --> 00:59:19,973
and something's
got to be done.

1450
00:59:20,057 --> 00:59:21,433
And that's not it.

1451
00:59:21,516 --> 00:59:24,186
Not even on my birthday?

1452
00:59:24,269 --> 00:59:25,312
Oh, well.

1453
00:59:25,395 --> 00:59:27,022
<i>Oh, darling,
don't you see?</i>

1454
00:59:27,105 --> 00:59:29,149
He'll get away
if you don't get busy.

1455
00:59:29,232 --> 00:59:30,692
I'm on my vacation.

1456
00:59:30,776 --> 00:59:32,402
Oh, Nicky, you're
driving me crazy.

1457
00:59:32,486 --> 00:59:33,945
This case
is serious,

1458
00:59:34,029 --> 00:59:36,823
and all you do is fuddle around
and guzzle cider.

1459
00:59:36,907 --> 00:59:39,034
I'll switch
to prune juice.

1460
00:59:39,117 --> 00:59:41,244
Alright. If you're going
to neglect your duty,

1461
00:59:41,328 --> 00:59:42,412
I'm not.

1462
00:59:42,496 --> 00:59:43,705
Brogan is
mixed up in this,

1463
00:59:43,789 --> 00:59:47,542
and i'm going to
find out how and why.

1464
00:59:47,626 --> 00:59:50,462
Bertram: Mr. Brogan,
have you any greeting cards

1465
00:59:50,545 --> 00:59:51,797
for a man going to bed?

1466
00:59:51,880 --> 00:59:53,131
No, but...

1467
00:59:53,215 --> 00:59:54,883
Well, you better
start working on them,

1468
00:59:54,966 --> 00:59:56,885
because that's
where i'm going.

1469
00:59:56,968 --> 00:59:58,720
I guess i'd better
mosey along, too.

1470
00:59:58,804 --> 00:59:59,888
Excuse me.

1471
00:59:59,971 --> 01:00:01,098
Must you go,
Mr. Brogan?

1472
01:00:01,181 --> 01:00:02,849
There's still
some cake left.

1473
01:00:02,933 --> 01:00:04,226
Thank you,
Mrs. Charles,

1474
01:00:04,309 --> 01:00:05,769
but you know
the old saying...

1475
01:00:05,852 --> 01:00:08,230
a man's eyes are often
bigger than his belly.

1476
01:00:08,313 --> 01:00:09,940
[laughing]
Good night.

1477
01:00:10,023 --> 01:00:11,733
Good night.
What a nice man.

1478
01:00:14,528 --> 01:00:16,655
I didn't mean to talk business
at your party, Nick.

1479
01:00:16,738 --> 01:00:18,281
But you know
there's many a slip

1480
01:00:18,365 --> 01:00:20,367
twixt the cup
and the lip.

1481
01:00:20,450 --> 01:00:21,868
Nora knows who committed
the murder.

1482
01:00:21,952 --> 01:00:23,495
- Yeah? Who?
- You.

1483
01:00:23,578 --> 01:00:26,289
Me?

1484
01:00:26,373 --> 01:00:28,125
Boy, that is
interesting.

1485
01:00:28,208 --> 01:00:30,043
Look, I think she's
going to trail you, see?

1486
01:00:30,127 --> 01:00:32,295
So, give her
a little exercise.

1487
01:00:32,379 --> 01:00:33,839
Take her for
a nice, long walk.

1488
01:00:33,922 --> 01:00:34,965
I've got something
i want to do.

1489
01:00:35,048 --> 01:00:36,216
I get it.

1490
01:00:38,969 --> 01:00:41,680
Nicky, I think i'll go
for a little walk.

1491
01:00:41,763 --> 01:00:43,265
Want me to go
with you?

1492
01:00:43,348 --> 01:00:45,725
No, no. I'm just going
to the drugstore.

1493
01:01:12,878 --> 01:01:14,171
Good night,
Nicky.

1494
01:01:14,254 --> 01:01:15,630
Oh, good night,
darling.

1495
01:01:15,714 --> 01:01:17,215
Now, try to get
to bed early.

1496
01:01:17,299 --> 01:01:18,925
You know me.

1497
01:01:19,009 --> 01:01:21,928
Hello, Bruce?
Nick Charles.

1498
01:01:22,012 --> 01:01:24,723
Uh, busy?

1499
01:01:24,806 --> 01:01:27,309
How'd you like to take me
out to Crazy Mary's?

1500
01:01:32,480 --> 01:01:34,191
Nick, remember when we used
to come up here fishing?

1501
01:01:34,274 --> 01:01:35,483
Yeah.

1502
01:01:35,567 --> 01:01:37,402
Boy, you sure
caught the big ones.

1503
01:01:37,485 --> 01:01:38,820
It's all in the flick
of the wrist.

1504
01:01:38,904 --> 01:01:40,822
I guess i never did
flick right.

1505
01:01:40,906 --> 01:01:42,449
You better stay in the car
till i call her.

1506
01:01:42,532 --> 01:01:43,950
You're liable to get
conked on the head.

1507
01:01:44,034 --> 01:01:46,203
Oh, Mary.

1508
01:01:46,286 --> 01:01:48,246
Yoo-hoo. Mary.

1509
01:01:48,330 --> 01:01:49,581
It's me, Dr. Clayworth.

1510
01:01:52,417 --> 01:01:54,336
Hello, Mary.
I just want to

1511
01:01:54,419 --> 01:01:56,630
talk to you for
a minute, huh?

1512
01:02:11,519 --> 01:02:13,271
Get out of here.
Get out!

1513
01:02:13,355 --> 01:02:15,065
Now, now, Mary.
Nobody's going to hurt you.

1514
01:02:15,148 --> 01:02:17,025
I don't want him
around here.

1515
01:02:17,108 --> 01:02:19,277
Why didn't you tell me
he was with you?

1516
01:02:19,361 --> 01:02:20,737
Get him out.

1517
01:02:20,820 --> 01:02:22,530
Now, he just wants to
ask you a few questions.

1518
01:02:22,614 --> 01:02:25,325
I'm not answering
any questions.

1519
01:02:25,408 --> 01:02:27,118
You leave me alone.
Do you hear?

1520
01:02:27,202 --> 01:02:28,495
You leave me alone.

1521
01:02:28,578 --> 01:02:31,164
I don't want to answer
any questions.

1522
01:02:31,248 --> 01:02:32,666
Now get out.

1523
01:02:32,749 --> 01:02:35,293
I want to talk to you
about Eleanor Morgan.

1524
01:02:37,128 --> 01:02:38,255
Eleanor Morgan?

1525
01:02:41,675 --> 01:02:44,344
I have a lot of
information, Mary,

1526
01:02:44,427 --> 01:02:46,179
from Boston.

1527
01:02:46,263 --> 01:02:48,515
You know about
Eleanor Morgan?

1528
01:02:48,598 --> 01:02:50,016
Yes.

1529
01:02:52,811 --> 01:02:55,105
Nobody knows
about Eleanor Morgan.

1530
01:02:55,188 --> 01:02:56,356
I do, Mary.

1531
01:03:10,704 --> 01:03:13,540
[sobs]

1532
01:03:13,623 --> 01:03:15,625
Peter know you were
his mother, Mary?

1533
01:03:15,709 --> 01:03:16,876
Mary: No.

1534
01:03:19,212 --> 01:03:21,214
But i watched over him
best i could.

1535
01:03:21,298 --> 01:03:23,633
Sure, you did.

1536
01:03:23,717 --> 01:03:26,428
Who do you think
killed him?

1537
01:03:26,511 --> 01:03:28,638
How should i know?

1538
01:03:31,182 --> 01:03:33,268
He had a fight with somebody
out at the auto camp,

1539
01:03:33,351 --> 01:03:34,811
gave him a couple
of black eyes.

1540
01:03:34,894 --> 01:03:36,688
Who was that?

1541
01:03:36,771 --> 01:03:38,815
Bill Burns
out at the plant.

1542
01:03:38,898 --> 01:03:41,860
What was
the fight about?

1543
01:03:41,943 --> 01:03:43,403
I ain"t gonna tell you nothing.
Now get out of here.

1544
01:03:43,486 --> 01:03:44,988
I'm trying to
help you, Mary.

1545
01:03:45,071 --> 01:03:47,032
Nobody's trying to help me.
They're all against me.

1546
01:03:47,115 --> 01:03:48,408
I know what they're after,
and they're not going to get it.

1547
01:03:48,491 --> 01:03:49,909
I'll get it first

1548
01:03:49,993 --> 01:03:52,037
because i know somebody
that'll get it for me.

1549
01:03:52,120 --> 01:03:54,414
If anybody else
comes nosing around,

1550
01:03:54,497 --> 01:03:56,666
they're going to get
something they don't like!

1551
01:03:56,750 --> 01:03:57,751
Now get out!

1552
01:03:57,834 --> 01:03:59,044
Now, now.
Alright, Mary.

1553
01:03:59,127 --> 01:04:00,920
Alright, we're going.
We're going.

1554
01:04:06,885 --> 01:04:08,845
Holy smoke.
Peter Berton's mother?

1555
01:04:08,928 --> 01:04:10,221
Mm-hmm.

1556
01:04:10,305 --> 01:04:12,349
Where does
the Eleanor Morgan come in?

1557
01:04:12,432 --> 01:04:13,850
That's the name she used

1558
01:04:13,933 --> 01:04:16,186
at the hospital in Boston
where he was born.

1559
01:04:16,269 --> 01:04:17,812
And later, when
she turned him over

1560
01:04:17,896 --> 01:04:20,148
to the children's home,
she used Berton.

1561
01:04:20,231 --> 01:04:21,649
Oh.

1562
01:04:21,733 --> 01:04:22,901
[vehicle approaching]

1563
01:04:27,155 --> 01:04:28,615
Hiya, Mac.

1564
01:04:28,698 --> 01:04:29,949
What delayed you?

1565
01:04:30,033 --> 01:04:31,326
For a guy who's
on his vacation,

1566
01:04:31,409 --> 01:04:32,869
you certainly
buzz around a lot.

1567
01:04:32,952 --> 01:04:34,245
I was looking
for you, Bruce.

1568
01:04:34,329 --> 01:04:35,705
I wanted you to come
out here with me.

1569
01:04:35,789 --> 01:04:37,165
Nick tried,
but he couldn't get anything.

1570
01:04:37,248 --> 01:04:40,001
Oh, yeah? Well, I'll get
something out of her.

1571
01:04:43,755 --> 01:04:45,590
He got something
out of her.

1572
01:04:48,927 --> 01:04:51,513
There. Okay?

1573
01:04:51,596 --> 01:04:53,139
Whoa.

1574
01:04:53,223 --> 01:04:54,391
[chuckles]

1575
01:05:36,266 --> 01:05:37,350
Hello.

1576
01:05:38,560 --> 01:05:40,478
- Hi.
- How are you?

1577
01:05:54,534 --> 01:05:55,618
Hi, cutie.

1578
01:05:55,702 --> 01:05:56,661
Hiya, babe.

1579
01:05:56,744 --> 01:05:57,954
Hello, sister.

1580
01:05:58,037 --> 01:05:59,414
Gentlemen...

1581
01:05:59,497 --> 01:06:00,707
Man: Say, ain't you with
that new burlesque show

1582
01:06:00,790 --> 01:06:02,208
down at The Grand?

1583
01:06:02,292 --> 01:06:04,461
There's my uncle.
I've got to go now.

1584
01:06:05,837 --> 01:06:07,172
Good-bye, cutie.

1585
01:06:07,255 --> 01:06:08,715
Good-bye.

1586
01:06:22,645 --> 01:06:23,897
Man: Yes, sir?

1587
01:06:23,980 --> 01:06:26,524
Oh, let's see now.
Where was i going?

1588
01:06:26,608 --> 01:06:28,526
Oh, yes. What time's
the next train to New York?

1589
01:06:28,610 --> 01:06:29,694
10:14.

1590
01:06:29,777 --> 01:06:31,070
Thank you.

1591
01:06:44,209 --> 01:06:45,877
That man who
was just here...

1592
01:06:45,960 --> 01:06:47,587
he was asking about
a train, wasn't he?

1593
01:06:47,670 --> 01:06:49,756
Yes, ma'am.
The 10:14 to New York.

1594
01:06:49,839 --> 01:06:51,299
Oh.

1595
01:07:00,600 --> 01:07:02,727
Give me a cup of coffee
and two aspirins.

1596
01:07:04,020 --> 01:07:06,231
Hello,
Mr. MacGregor.

1597
01:07:06,314 --> 01:07:07,857
I'm so glad
you're here.

1598
01:07:07,941 --> 01:07:10,485
Always glad to see a member
of the Charles family.

1599
01:07:10,568 --> 01:07:12,320
There's a man here.
I want you to arrest him.

1600
01:07:12,403 --> 01:07:13,571
What for?

1601
01:07:13,655 --> 01:07:14,864
Does it have to be
for something?

1602
01:07:14,948 --> 01:07:17,075
Oh, no. No.

1603
01:07:17,158 --> 01:07:18,618
You just pick out
anybody at all,

1604
01:07:18,701 --> 01:07:20,703
and i put them
in jail for life.

1605
01:07:20,787 --> 01:07:22,580
But this man's
going to leave town.

1606
01:07:22,664 --> 01:07:25,333
Look, Mrs. Charles,
I had a little business

1607
01:07:25,416 --> 01:07:27,085
with your husband
a while ago,

1608
01:07:27,168 --> 01:07:29,295
and i got a big
headache out of it.

1609
01:07:29,379 --> 01:07:31,005
I can't arrest
anybody for you

1610
01:07:31,089 --> 01:07:33,383
unless they do something
to get arrested.

1611
01:07:33,466 --> 01:07:37,303
Get that?
They got to do something.

1612
01:07:37,387 --> 01:07:40,056
I think you're being very
technical, Mr. MacGregor.

1613
01:07:42,350 --> 01:07:44,686
Make that four aspirin.

1614
01:08:04,622 --> 01:08:06,040
[wolf whistles]

1615
01:08:12,005 --> 01:08:14,132
Jeez, lady,
what's the idea?

1616
01:08:14,215 --> 01:08:15,800
Looking for somebody,
sister?

1617
01:08:15,883 --> 01:08:17,677
[men whistling]

1618
01:08:57,759 --> 01:08:59,636
[men whistling]

1619
01:09:02,096 --> 01:09:03,723
Say, what have you
got against me?

1620
01:09:03,806 --> 01:09:05,600
Oh, I'm so sorry.

1621
01:09:15,151 --> 01:09:16,486
Sorry, lady,
but we don't allow

1622
01:09:16,569 --> 01:09:18,363
no unescorted
females in here.

1623
01:09:18,446 --> 01:09:20,531
Isn't that an old-fashioned
point of view?

1624
01:09:20,615 --> 01:09:22,575
I mean, after all,
times have changed.

1625
01:09:22,659 --> 01:09:24,369
She's with me,
bartender.

1626
01:09:24,452 --> 01:09:26,746
Two beers,
and hurry it up.

1627
01:09:26,829 --> 01:09:28,790
I hope you don't mind
my barging in like this.

1628
01:09:28,873 --> 01:09:30,708
Oh, that's
quite alright.

1629
01:09:30,792 --> 01:09:32,460
Pool rooms
are so informal.

1630
01:09:32,543 --> 01:09:33,836
Well, I wanted
to talk to you.

1631
01:09:33,920 --> 01:09:35,963
You see, as a matter
of fact,

1632
01:09:36,047 --> 01:09:37,382
I've been
following you.

1633
01:09:37,465 --> 01:09:38,675
You've been
following me?

1634
01:09:38,758 --> 01:09:39,759
Ever since you
left the house.

1635
01:09:39,842 --> 01:09:41,344
It's silly. I know.

1636
01:09:41,427 --> 01:09:44,013
But my wife has got her
heart set on a picture,

1637
01:09:44,097 --> 01:09:45,890
one you bought
at the Crump Art Shop,

1638
01:09:45,973 --> 01:09:48,559
and i'd like to buy
that painting from you.

1639
01:09:48,643 --> 01:09:51,354
Painting?
Oh, the windmill.

1640
01:09:51,437 --> 01:09:53,272
Yes. Personally,
I don't like it,

1641
01:09:53,356 --> 01:09:54,732
but my wife
is keen about it,

1642
01:09:54,816 --> 01:09:56,359
so i'm prepared
to pay you a good price.

1643
01:09:56,442 --> 01:09:57,402
A good price?

1644
01:09:57,485 --> 01:09:58,611
Say, $500.

1645
01:09:58,695 --> 01:10:02,073
$500? Well, I only
paid $60 for it.

1646
01:10:02,156 --> 01:10:05,284
You can't make any money
paying $500 for a $60 painting.

1647
01:10:05,368 --> 01:10:07,078
Well, money doesn't
matter when it comes

1648
01:10:07,161 --> 01:10:09,038
to making the little
woman happy.

1649
01:10:09,122 --> 01:10:11,708
That's a fine quality
in a husband, mister...

1650
01:10:11,791 --> 01:10:14,168
Draque.
Edgar Draque.

1651
01:10:14,252 --> 01:10:15,503
Then it's a deal?

1652
01:10:15,586 --> 01:10:16,713
Well...

1653
01:10:16,796 --> 01:10:18,005
Fine. Can i get
the painting now?

1654
01:10:18,089 --> 01:10:20,341
Not now. I'll get it
for you later.

1655
01:10:20,425 --> 01:10:21,759
I'll bring it to you.

1656
01:10:21,843 --> 01:10:23,761
Well, I'd like to get it
as soon as possible.

1657
01:10:23,845 --> 01:10:25,471
I'm stopping at
the Sycamore Springs Hotel.

1658
01:10:25,555 --> 01:10:26,514
If you'd care to...

1659
01:10:26,597 --> 01:10:28,099
The Sycamore Springs Hotel...

1660
01:10:28,182 --> 01:10:29,600
That's where they're
holding the Charity Bazaar.

1661
01:10:29,684 --> 01:10:31,728
That's right.
I have to leave town tonight,

1662
01:10:31,811 --> 01:10:33,563
and i'd like to get
the painting before i go.

1663
01:10:34,939 --> 01:10:37,358
You beast!

1664
01:10:37,442 --> 01:10:39,110
This man insulted me!

1665
01:10:42,029 --> 01:10:43,781
Break it up!
Hold it, you guys!

1666
01:10:43,865 --> 01:10:45,658
Break it up there!

1667
01:10:51,581 --> 01:10:53,040
My, my.

1668
01:10:54,208 --> 01:10:57,128
[commotion]

1669
01:11:02,425 --> 01:11:04,719
Uh, get me the police
department, please.

1670
01:11:06,429 --> 01:11:08,306
There's no use
denying it.

1671
01:11:08,389 --> 01:11:10,475
You did have a fight
with Peter Berton.

1672
01:11:10,558 --> 01:11:11,517
Yeah.

1673
01:11:11,601 --> 01:11:12,852
Hmm. Looks to me

1674
01:11:12,935 --> 01:11:15,104
as if you got more
than your share.

1675
01:11:15,188 --> 01:11:16,439
All i'm asking is,

1676
01:11:16,522 --> 01:11:18,524
what was
the fight about?

1677
01:11:18,608 --> 01:11:21,277
Well, Mr. Charles,
it seems to me

1678
01:11:21,360 --> 01:11:24,447
that's nobody's business
but Berton's and mine.

1679
01:11:24,530 --> 01:11:27,825
Now that he's dead,
it's only mine.

1680
01:11:27,909 --> 01:11:29,869
Why didn't you like him?

1681
01:11:29,952 --> 01:11:31,120
Well, I like people

1682
01:11:31,204 --> 01:11:33,831
that are straightforward
and honest.

1683
01:11:33,915 --> 01:11:35,958
I want to be able
to peg them.

1684
01:11:36,042 --> 01:11:39,212
If i can't peg them,
I don't like them.

1685
01:11:42,381 --> 01:11:43,716
I see.

1686
01:11:43,800 --> 01:11:45,384
Well, if that's all
you're going to ask me,

1687
01:11:45,468 --> 01:11:48,346
I think i'll be
going along.

1688
01:11:48,429 --> 01:11:50,056
The fact
that the boy's dead

1689
01:11:50,139 --> 01:11:52,892
<i>doesn't seem to have made
very much impression on you.</i>

1690
01:11:52,975 --> 01:11:54,310
Why should it?

1691
01:11:54,393 --> 01:11:55,478
Death hasn't
endowed him

1692
01:11:55,561 --> 01:11:58,022
with any new
virtues, has it?

1693
01:11:58,105 --> 01:12:00,566
Well, that's a little brutal,
but, uh, honest.

1694
01:12:02,026 --> 01:12:03,569
Do you, uh...

1695
01:12:03,653 --> 01:12:04,946
do you know of anyone

1696
01:12:05,029 --> 01:12:06,656
who might have had
cause to Kill him?

1697
01:12:06,739 --> 01:12:08,574
The way he was cutting throats
at the plant,

1698
01:12:08,658 --> 01:12:10,159
there might have been
a number of people.

1699
01:12:10,243 --> 01:12:11,911
What about you?

1700
01:12:13,830 --> 01:12:16,207
Mr. Charles, when you've
got anything on me,

1701
01:12:16,290 --> 01:12:17,667
you can serve
your papers,

1702
01:12:17,750 --> 01:12:19,043
but until that time,

1703
01:12:19,126 --> 01:12:21,045
I figure my time
is my own.

1704
01:12:27,510 --> 01:12:28,803
What did he want?

1705
01:12:28,886 --> 01:12:30,721
He just wanted to
ask me a few questions.

1706
01:12:30,805 --> 01:12:31,806
Questions about what?

1707
01:12:33,307 --> 01:12:34,559
Come on, Asta.

1708
01:12:34,642 --> 01:12:36,185
[vehicle approaching]

1709
01:12:39,105 --> 01:12:41,566
Nicky, come on.
Come on.

1710
01:12:41,649 --> 01:12:43,442
- Huh?
- Don't stand there stargazing.

1711
01:12:43,526 --> 01:12:45,111
- We've got to hurry.
- Hurry? Where to?

1712
01:12:45,194 --> 01:12:47,905
We're going to a dance.

1713
01:12:47,989 --> 01:12:50,074
He offered me $500 for it.

1714
01:12:50,157 --> 01:12:51,242
$500 for a dance?

1715
01:12:51,325 --> 01:12:52,451
And it was right there

1716
01:12:52,535 --> 01:12:53,870
under your nose
all the time, too.

1717
01:12:53,953 --> 01:12:55,454
- Under my nose?
- Nicky, we've got to hurry.

1718
01:12:55,538 --> 01:12:56,706
I had him thrown in jail,
but he might get out,

1719
01:12:56,789 --> 01:12:57,832
and then he'd get
the painting.

1720
01:12:57,915 --> 01:12:58,875
Jail? Painting?

1721
01:12:58,958 --> 01:13:00,418
Sycamore Springs Hotel.

1722
01:13:00,501 --> 01:13:02,879
I figured as long
as i had one man arrested,

1723
01:13:02,962 --> 01:13:05,798
I might as well have
him locked up, too.

1724
01:13:05,882 --> 01:13:08,175
Did you do all this
on cider?

1725
01:13:12,805 --> 01:13:15,224
[ballroom music]

1726
01:13:20,187 --> 01:13:21,314
I thought you'd be
proud of me,

1727
01:13:21,397 --> 01:13:22,607
killing two birds
with one stone.

1728
01:13:22,690 --> 01:13:23,733
Two birds?

1729
01:13:23,816 --> 01:13:24,901
Yes. They're both in jail.

1730
01:13:24,984 --> 01:13:27,153
- Who's the other?
- Brogan.

1731
01:13:27,236 --> 01:13:28,654
- Brogan's in jail?
- Yes.

1732
01:13:28,738 --> 01:13:29,906
[indistinct chatter]

1733
01:13:33,409 --> 01:13:35,286
Nick: I'll split my business
up among you...

1734
01:13:35,369 --> 01:13:37,079
a gift to the boys.

1735
01:13:37,163 --> 01:13:38,706
Good evening,
Mr. Charles.

1736
01:13:38,789 --> 01:13:40,082
Hello.

1737
01:13:40,166 --> 01:13:41,751
I bet you think
i'm a silly little girl

1738
01:13:41,834 --> 01:13:43,419
for behaving the way
i did at the house.

1739
01:13:43,502 --> 01:13:45,212
You were perfectly right
to be angry with me.

1740
01:13:45,296 --> 01:13:46,505
I'm not angry with you.

1741
01:13:46,589 --> 01:13:47,757
Oh, aren't you really?

1742
01:13:47,840 --> 01:13:49,258
No. Here. I'll
prove it to you.

1743
01:13:49,342 --> 01:13:50,468
I'll take
all your tickets.

1744
01:13:50,551 --> 01:13:51,677
You can prove it
even better

1745
01:13:51,761 --> 01:13:53,679
by dancing with me.

1746
01:13:53,763 --> 01:13:55,222
Alright, put me
down for a dance.

1747
01:13:55,306 --> 01:13:57,099
Oh, do you jitterbug?

1748
01:13:57,183 --> 01:13:59,769
No. Put me down
for a slow polka.

1749
01:14:01,938 --> 01:14:03,230
Was that necessary?

1750
01:14:03,314 --> 01:14:04,899
Do you have to shine up
to him like that?

1751
01:14:04,982 --> 01:14:07,777
Oh, Tom,
you're impossible.

1752
01:14:07,860 --> 01:14:09,654
Nicky, it's gone.

1753
01:14:09,737 --> 01:14:10,947
Huh? What's gone?

1754
01:14:11,030 --> 01:14:12,323
The painting i gave you.

1755
01:14:12,406 --> 01:14:13,699
The painting you gave me?

1756
01:14:13,783 --> 01:14:15,534
I mean, the painting
i didn't give you.

1757
01:14:15,618 --> 01:14:17,328
The paint... come again?

1758
01:14:17,411 --> 01:14:19,163
For your birthday.

1759
01:14:19,246 --> 01:14:21,415
The painting that you gave me
but you didn't give me...

1760
01:14:21,499 --> 01:14:22,792
[ululating]

1761
01:14:22,875 --> 01:14:25,169
I beg your pardon.
I didn't understand.

1762
01:14:25,252 --> 01:14:27,088
Gracious me! What are you
doing in here?

1763
01:14:27,171 --> 01:14:28,631
Don't you remember me?

1764
01:14:28,714 --> 01:14:29,924
I'm looking for the
painting of the windmill.

1765
01:14:30,007 --> 01:14:31,801
The windmill?
Everybody's looking

1766
01:14:31,884 --> 01:14:33,135
for the painting
of the windmill.

1767
01:14:33,219 --> 01:14:35,054
Now, you get
out of here.

1768
01:14:35,137 --> 01:14:36,347
Goodness gracious!

1769
01:14:36,430 --> 01:14:37,723
All a painter has
to do nowadays

1770
01:14:37,807 --> 01:14:38,933
is to get killed

1771
01:14:39,016 --> 01:14:41,102
and suddenly
becomes a genius.

1772
01:14:41,185 --> 01:14:42,520
Did you say
the painter was killed?

1773
01:14:42,603 --> 01:14:45,815
Yes. Peter Berton,
all higgledy-piggledy.

1774
01:14:45,898 --> 01:14:47,400
Was that painting
by Peter Berton?

1775
01:14:47,483 --> 01:14:48,818
Gracious me, yes.

1776
01:14:48,901 --> 01:14:50,611
Everybody's been
after that painting.

1777
01:14:50,695 --> 01:14:53,364
First the blonde,
then Sam Ronson, and now you.

1778
01:14:53,447 --> 01:14:54,490
- Sam Ronson?
- Yes.

1779
01:14:54,573 --> 01:14:56,409
Well, where is it?

1780
01:14:56,492 --> 01:14:59,161
I sold it to the blonde.

1781
01:14:59,245 --> 01:15:01,664
Mr. Crump, what was
the blonde's name?

1782
01:15:02,915 --> 01:15:05,126
Mrs. Edgar Draque.

1783
01:15:05,209 --> 01:15:06,669
Crump: She lives here
in the hotel.

1784
01:15:06,752 --> 01:15:08,462
Draque. That's
the name of the man

1785
01:15:08,546 --> 01:15:10,381
who offered me
the $500.

1786
01:15:12,008 --> 01:15:14,176
- Uh... wait here.
- Where are you going?

1787
01:15:14,260 --> 01:15:15,886
I want to do a little business
with the blonde.

1788
01:15:15,970 --> 01:15:17,096
You think she'll
give it to you?

1789
01:15:17,179 --> 01:15:18,472
I can try, darling.

1790
01:15:18,556 --> 01:15:20,057
Anything for art.
I'll be right back.

1791
01:15:20,141 --> 01:15:21,892
No. I think i'll go
along and chaperone.

1792
01:15:21,976 --> 01:15:24,979
Well, uh...
Oh, hello, sailor.

1793
01:15:25,062 --> 01:15:26,230
Why aren't you
dancing?

1794
01:15:26,313 --> 01:15:27,773
I haven't got
any dance tickets.

1795
01:15:27,857 --> 01:15:30,317
No dance tickets?
Well, of course you have.

1796
01:15:30,401 --> 01:15:31,527
[chuckles]

1797
01:15:32,903 --> 01:15:34,196
There you are,
and here's your partner.

1798
01:15:34,280 --> 01:15:35,406
Gee, thanks.

1799
01:15:35,489 --> 01:15:37,283
Nicky!

1800
01:15:37,366 --> 01:15:38,451
Nicky!

1801
01:15:41,662 --> 01:15:44,582
[instrumental music]

1802
01:16:02,850 --> 01:16:05,770
Uh, what's the number
of Mr. Draque's room?

1803
01:16:05,853 --> 01:16:07,188
One-twenty-four.

1804
01:16:07,271 --> 01:16:08,481
One-twenty-four. Thanks.

1805
01:16:23,412 --> 01:16:24,538
- Good evening, Mr. Charles.
- Good evening, Willoughby.

1806
01:16:24,622 --> 01:16:25,790
Hello.

1807
01:16:25,873 --> 01:16:27,583
I see you've decided
to stay in town.

1808
01:16:27,666 --> 01:16:29,585
I never had any
intention of leaving.

1809
01:16:29,668 --> 01:16:31,587
- By the way, Tatum...
- Yeah?

1810
01:16:31,670 --> 01:16:33,589
When the hospital's built,
you must come in

1811
01:16:33,672 --> 01:16:35,341
and have my father
treat your nose.

1812
01:16:35,424 --> 01:16:37,218
There's nothing wrong
with my nose.

1813
01:16:37,301 --> 01:16:38,803
There will be.

1814
01:16:46,393 --> 01:16:48,395
[knocks]

1815
01:17:24,807 --> 01:17:26,892
Oh, pardon me.

1816
01:17:26,976 --> 01:17:28,936
Come in.
Come in, dear.

1817
01:17:29,019 --> 01:17:30,563
It's Mrs. Draque.

1818
01:17:30,646 --> 01:17:32,398
How do you do,
Mrs. Draque?

1819
01:17:32,481 --> 01:17:35,693
Well, you certainly
got right down to business.

1820
01:17:35,776 --> 01:17:38,487
I found her on the floor.

1821
01:17:38,571 --> 01:17:39,864
She was out cold.

1822
01:17:39,947 --> 01:17:41,699
Somebody had conked her
before i got here.

1823
01:17:41,782 --> 01:17:42,950
What about
the painting?

1824
01:17:43,033 --> 01:17:45,202
It's gone.
We're going after it.

1825
01:17:45,286 --> 01:17:47,454
I'm glad to have met you,
Mrs. Draque.

1826
01:17:47,538 --> 01:17:49,456
- Clerk.
- Yes, sir?

1827
01:17:49,540 --> 01:17:51,333
You better have someone
go up to 124.

1828
01:17:51,417 --> 01:17:52,543
What's wrong?

1829
01:17:52,626 --> 01:17:54,795
Mrs. Draque
is... indisposed.

1830
01:17:54,879 --> 01:17:56,046
Alright.

1831
01:17:56,130 --> 01:17:58,257
Now, let me think.
Ah, let's see.

1832
01:17:58,340 --> 01:17:59,341
Peter Berton painted it.

1833
01:17:59,425 --> 01:18:00,843
Everybody wanted it.

1834
01:18:00,926 --> 01:18:03,429
Draque offered 500.
Mrs. Draque got it.

1835
01:18:03,512 --> 01:18:04,680
She got conked.

1836
01:18:05,890 --> 01:18:07,516
Hmm... let's see, now.

1837
01:18:07,600 --> 01:18:09,560
Who else wanted it?

1838
01:18:09,643 --> 01:18:11,228
Crazy Mary said
she knew somebody

1839
01:18:11,312 --> 01:18:13,063
who would get it for her.

1840
01:18:13,147 --> 01:18:14,899
That might be it.

1841
01:18:14,982 --> 01:18:17,276
There's Ronson.

1842
01:18:17,359 --> 01:18:19,904
Ronson. Ronson said
he wanted it, too.

1843
01:18:21,447 --> 01:18:22,573
Yes.

1844
01:18:23,782 --> 01:18:25,492
There's the doc.

1845
01:18:27,286 --> 01:18:29,330
Bruce. Excuse me.
Are you busy?

1846
01:18:29,413 --> 01:18:30,539
Well, we're going
to have a dance.

1847
01:18:30,623 --> 01:18:31,665
Say, how would you
like to take me

1848
01:18:31,749 --> 01:18:32,750
for another little ride?

1849
01:18:32,833 --> 01:18:34,043
Well, I'd like to, but...

1850
01:18:34,126 --> 01:18:35,878
Oh, that's fine.
Come on, let's go.

1851
01:18:35,961 --> 01:18:36,921
Where are we going?

1852
01:18:37,004 --> 01:18:38,130
Crazy Mary's.

1853
01:18:38,214 --> 01:18:39,215
That's where we belong.

1854
01:18:39,298 --> 01:18:40,883
Come on, Asta.

1855
01:18:50,893 --> 01:18:54,188
Nora: Dr. Clayworth
is going to miss all the dances.

1856
01:18:54,271 --> 01:18:56,023
Don't worry about me.

1857
01:18:56,106 --> 01:18:58,108
I'm not much
of a dancer anyway.

1858
01:19:00,152 --> 01:19:01,362
Nick was the one

1859
01:19:01,445 --> 01:19:03,405
the girls always
wanted to dance with.

1860
01:19:03,489 --> 01:19:05,866
I hear he also
played the banjo.

1861
01:19:27,221 --> 01:19:28,222
She's dead.

1862
01:19:28,305 --> 01:19:30,557
Nicky. Nicky, look.

1863
01:19:39,066 --> 01:19:40,401
Shot with her own gun.

1864
01:19:40,484 --> 01:19:41,694
Hey, that's one way

1865
01:19:41,777 --> 01:19:42,945
of destroying
fingerprints, huh?

1866
01:19:43,028 --> 01:19:44,113
It certainly is, yes.

1867
01:19:44,196 --> 01:19:45,948
We'd better call MacGregor.

1868
01:19:46,031 --> 01:19:47,533
[Asta barking]

1869
01:19:47,616 --> 01:19:48,742
Asta.

1870
01:19:48,826 --> 01:19:50,619
Nora: Asta, what is it?

1871
01:19:50,703 --> 01:19:52,997
[barking continues]

1872
01:19:56,834 --> 01:19:58,252
Nora: That's it!

1873
01:19:58,335 --> 01:20:00,254
Your birthday present.

1874
01:20:03,215 --> 01:20:06,260
Asta, you'll get
an extra bone for this.

1875
01:20:06,343 --> 01:20:08,137
[growling playfully]

1876
01:20:11,849 --> 01:20:13,267
Nicky.

1877
01:20:13,350 --> 01:20:15,060
Hey, what are you
doing up this hour?

1878
01:20:15,144 --> 01:20:16,854
I came down
to ask you that.

1879
01:20:16,937 --> 01:20:20,190
Well, I was still concentrating
on this little gem.

1880
01:20:20,274 --> 01:20:22,568
Funny thing to concentrate on
at this hour of the night.

1881
01:20:22,651 --> 01:20:25,029
Why don't you tackle it in
the morning when you're fresher?

1882
01:20:28,115 --> 01:20:30,451
Say, you're pretty
fresh right now.

1883
01:20:32,244 --> 01:20:34,246
You know, this has
to be solved by morning.

1884
01:20:34,330 --> 01:20:35,873
We're in
the home stretch.

1885
01:20:35,956 --> 01:20:38,125
How's it look
for the finish?

1886
01:20:38,208 --> 01:20:41,462
Well, I'm not passing out
any tips just yet.

1887
01:20:41,545 --> 01:20:42,671
A secret.

1888
01:20:42,755 --> 01:20:43,922
Mm-hmm.

1889
01:20:44,006 --> 01:20:45,591
Worried?

1890
01:20:45,674 --> 01:20:49,261
Say, you are
worried, aren't you?

1891
01:20:49,345 --> 01:20:52,556
Oh, I've handled
trickier shows than this.

1892
01:20:52,639 --> 01:20:55,309
But your old man wasn't
in the audience watching you.

1893
01:20:55,392 --> 01:20:57,686
That's it, isn't it?
Or a part of it, anyway.

1894
01:20:57,770 --> 01:20:58,896
Hmm.

1895
01:21:00,230 --> 01:21:01,690
Ah. You'll get it.

1896
01:21:01,774 --> 01:21:03,692
You may not be any great
shakes as a detective,

1897
01:21:03,776 --> 01:21:07,237
but you're lucky.
You'll solve it.

1898
01:21:07,321 --> 01:21:09,323
And your father will
be proud of you.

1899
01:21:09,406 --> 01:21:11,075
Mm-hmm.

1900
01:21:11,158 --> 01:21:13,243
He'd better be,
unless he wants to hear

1901
01:21:13,327 --> 01:21:14,995
that Stinky Davis
story again.

1902
01:21:15,079 --> 01:21:18,499
Oh, no, no, no.

1903
01:21:18,582 --> 01:21:21,251
Not that, dear. Not that.

1904
01:21:21,335 --> 01:21:23,170
I'll be waiting
for you, darling.

1905
01:21:23,253 --> 01:21:24,463
Good luck.

1906
01:21:24,546 --> 01:21:25,839
I'll need it, sister.

1907
01:21:25,923 --> 01:21:27,758
And don't call me sister.

1908
01:21:29,635 --> 01:21:30,803
Mother: Sit down.

1909
01:21:30,886 --> 01:21:32,888
Make yourself comfortable.

1910
01:21:37,017 --> 01:21:38,769
I demand to know
why we were brought here.

1911
01:21:38,852 --> 01:21:40,229
Nick Charles' orders.

1912
01:21:40,312 --> 01:21:42,606
I demand to see Nick Charles.
Where is he?

1913
01:21:42,689 --> 01:21:43,941
Search me.

1914
01:21:44,024 --> 01:21:45,526
I demand to know
what those people

1915
01:21:45,609 --> 01:21:47,069
are doing in
my laboratory.

1916
01:21:47,152 --> 01:21:48,320
I don't know.

1917
01:21:48,404 --> 01:21:49,738
<i>- Where's Nick Charles?
- I don't know.</i>

1918
01:21:49,822 --> 01:21:51,281
You don't know
much, do you?

1919
01:21:51,365 --> 01:21:53,450
<i>No, but
don't have to.</i>

1920
01:21:53,534 --> 01:21:54,618
Mrs. Green's
little boy

1921
01:21:54,701 --> 01:21:56,537
has just swallowed
50 cents.

1922
01:21:58,038 --> 01:21:59,206
[doorbell buzzes]

1923
01:21:59,289 --> 01:22:00,916
I'll get it, Hilda.

1924
01:22:03,627 --> 01:22:05,796
Hello, sister.
Nick Charles here?

1925
01:22:05,879 --> 01:22:07,798
- Who wants him?
- Yeah, who wants him?

1926
01:22:07,881 --> 01:22:09,299
Is your name sister?

1927
01:22:09,383 --> 01:22:10,634
Where's Nick Charles?
He's a friend of ours.

1928
01:22:10,717 --> 01:22:11,760
What do you want?

1929
01:22:11,844 --> 01:22:13,137
Pull in your ears, pop.

1930
01:22:13,220 --> 01:22:14,555
Now, listen, you.
You behave yourself.

1931
01:22:14,638 --> 01:22:15,722
You leave him alone.

1932
01:22:15,806 --> 01:22:17,724
Look, bub,
he sent for us.

1933
01:22:17,808 --> 01:22:18,892
What's your names?

1934
01:22:18,976 --> 01:22:20,102
My name's
Slugs Lonnegan.

1935
01:22:20,185 --> 01:22:21,687
His is Finnigan.
Mickey to you.

1936
01:22:21,770 --> 01:22:23,063
Yeah.

1937
01:22:23,147 --> 01:22:24,606
Why didn't you say so?

1938
01:22:24,690 --> 01:22:26,525
Go on in there
and sit down.

1939
01:22:26,608 --> 01:22:28,986
And keep quiet.

1940
01:22:29,069 --> 01:22:31,071
Is it always
like this, Nora?

1941
01:22:31,155 --> 01:22:32,448
Always.

1942
01:22:32,531 --> 01:22:34,158
You have
my deepest sympathy.

1943
01:22:35,617 --> 01:22:36,827
Mrs. Charles,
where is your husband?

1944
01:22:36,910 --> 01:22:38,537
I don't know.

1945
01:22:38,620 --> 01:22:40,789
Why don't you sit down
and take it easy, Mr. Ronson?

1946
01:22:40,873 --> 01:22:43,375
I'll just make some cocoa
to quiet their nerves.

1947
01:22:43,459 --> 01:22:45,752
Cocoa? What a break.

1948
01:22:45,836 --> 01:22:47,087
Ronson: I'd like to know
why it's necessary

1949
01:22:47,171 --> 01:22:48,797
to herd us all
into a room like this.

1950
01:22:48,881 --> 01:22:50,632
For a very simple
reason, Mr. Ronson.

1951
01:22:50,716 --> 01:22:52,217
This is the way
he always works,

1952
01:22:52,301 --> 01:22:54,928
and this time, he has
a very special reason.

1953
01:22:55,012 --> 01:22:57,973
Whatever he does, no matter
how idiotic it may seem,

1954
01:22:58,056 --> 01:23:00,559
nobody ever
outguesses him for long.

1955
01:23:00,642 --> 01:23:03,103
Just wait. You're going to be
mighty proud of him.

1956
01:23:03,187 --> 01:23:04,897
I've seen him work
on situations like this

1957
01:23:04,980 --> 01:23:06,482
that look
completely hopeless,

1958
01:23:06,565 --> 01:23:08,400
when suddenly the guilty
party cracks up

1959
01:23:08,484 --> 01:23:10,527
and starts trying
to shoot his way out.

1960
01:23:10,611 --> 01:23:11,778
But he's not going
to turn this place

1961
01:23:11,862 --> 01:23:13,280
into a shooting gallery?

1962
01:23:13,363 --> 01:23:15,240
That's the way these
things usually wind up.

1963
01:23:15,324 --> 01:23:16,658
It's called the payoff.

1964
01:23:16,742 --> 01:23:18,702
I usually duck under
the sofa when it starts.

1965
01:23:18,785 --> 01:23:20,120
It's outrageous,

1966
01:23:20,204 --> 01:23:22,206
treating people in this
high-handed fashion.

1967
01:23:22,289 --> 01:23:23,499
Where is he?

1968
01:23:23,582 --> 01:23:24,875
Oh, he's probably
arranging

1969
01:23:24,958 --> 01:23:26,960
a few surprises for us.

1970
01:23:27,044 --> 01:23:29,922
Right now, it may be part
of a strategy of nerves

1971
01:23:30,005 --> 01:23:31,632
to keep us all on edge,

1972
01:23:31,715 --> 01:23:33,175
but when the stage
is set,

1973
01:23:33,258 --> 01:23:35,344
he'll make
a dramatic entrance.

1974
01:23:35,427 --> 01:23:38,138
I'm usually nervous, too,
but this time i'm not.

1975
01:23:38,222 --> 01:23:39,556
You see,
I know who it is.

1976
01:23:39,640 --> 01:23:40,849
You do?

1977
01:23:40,933 --> 01:23:42,100
Well, who is it?

1978
01:23:43,769 --> 01:23:45,771
Wouldn't you like to know?

1979
01:23:45,854 --> 01:23:47,147
Ah.

1980
01:23:47,231 --> 01:23:48,398
There he is.

1981
01:23:48,482 --> 01:23:49,858
And mighty beautiful
timing, I'd say.

1982
01:23:49,942 --> 01:23:52,152
Hiya, Slugs, Mickey.
Got them, huh?

1983
01:23:52,236 --> 01:23:53,487
All here.

1984
01:23:53,570 --> 01:23:54,530
Good. Suppose you
unwrap them, huh?

1985
01:23:54,613 --> 01:23:56,615
Sure.

1986
01:23:56,698 --> 01:23:58,575
Sorry i had to keep
you all waiting.

1987
01:23:58,659 --> 01:24:02,287
I just want to ask you
a very few simple questions...

1988
01:24:02,371 --> 01:24:05,249
nothing really difficult
or involved,

1989
01:24:05,332 --> 01:24:07,042
just some little things,

1990
01:24:07,125 --> 01:24:10,170
and i'm sure you will all
want to help.

1991
01:24:11,755 --> 01:24:14,049
Mr. Draque,
you like it?

1992
01:24:14,132 --> 01:24:17,094
A genuine Berton,
Mrs. Draque.

1993
01:24:17,177 --> 01:24:19,429
By the way,
how's your head?

1994
01:24:24,726 --> 01:24:27,187
That mean anything
to you, Willoughby?

1995
01:24:27,271 --> 01:24:28,897
To me, no.

1996
01:24:28,981 --> 01:24:30,566
It will.

1997
01:24:33,860 --> 01:24:36,363
Mr. Ronson, does it
mean anything to you?

1998
01:24:36,446 --> 01:24:37,489
No.

1999
01:24:37,573 --> 01:24:39,241
- Sure?
- Of course i am.

2000
01:24:39,324 --> 01:24:41,243
Alright.
I'm just asking.

2001
01:24:41,326 --> 01:24:43,370
Uh-oh.
Ronson's cooked.

2002
01:24:43,453 --> 01:24:45,998
Mr. Crump, does that
mean anything to you?

2003
01:24:46,081 --> 01:24:48,834
Gracious me, yes.
Squidgey, isn't it?

2004
01:24:48,917 --> 01:24:50,085
Mmm, worse than that.

2005
01:24:50,168 --> 01:24:51,628
Precisely,
yes, yes, yes.

2006
01:24:51,712 --> 01:24:53,922
Now i'm about to demonstrate
something to you,

2007
01:24:54,006 --> 01:24:56,550
and in order to do it,
the room will have to be dark.

2008
01:24:56,633 --> 01:24:59,386
I hope you don't mind my taking
a few ordinary precautions,

2009
01:24:59,469 --> 01:25:01,013
but sometimes
people have a habit

2010
01:25:01,096 --> 01:25:04,433
of carrying firearms.
So, Mac, will you take over?

2011
01:25:04,516 --> 01:25:06,059
Everybody's
going to be searched.

2012
01:25:06,143 --> 01:25:07,561
Frisk them.

2013
01:25:07,644 --> 01:25:09,479
He can't do that.
There won't be any payoff.

2014
01:25:09,563 --> 01:25:10,856
Now, look here.
This is going too far.

2015
01:25:10,939 --> 01:25:13,400
Nick, stop being absurd.

2016
01:25:13,483 --> 01:25:15,027
These people
aren't criminals.

2017
01:25:15,110 --> 01:25:16,695
They're respectable
citizens.

2018
01:25:16,778 --> 01:25:18,864
They don't walk
around with guns.

2019
01:25:18,947 --> 01:25:20,824
MacGregor: Here's one.

2020
01:25:20,907 --> 01:25:21,950
As superintendent
at the plant,

2021
01:25:22,034 --> 01:25:23,076
I handle the payrolls,

2022
01:25:23,160 --> 01:25:24,369
and i need it
for protection.

2023
01:25:24,453 --> 01:25:26,330
This is a .45 army colt.

2024
01:25:26,413 --> 01:25:28,373
That's the same kind of a gun
killed Peter Berton.

2025
01:25:28,457 --> 01:25:31,376
Let me out of here!
I've got to get out of here!

2026
01:25:31,460 --> 01:25:33,086
Wait a minute.
Take it easy.

2027
01:25:33,170 --> 01:25:35,297
You can't hold me.
You've got nothing against me.

2028
01:25:35,380 --> 01:25:37,257
I've got a very important
appointment.

2029
01:25:37,341 --> 01:25:38,759
Well, your appointment
will have to wait.

2030
01:25:38,842 --> 01:25:40,636
It can't wait.
Really, it can't.

2031
01:25:40,719 --> 01:25:42,387
With whom was
your appointment?

2032
01:25:42,471 --> 01:25:43,847
I can't tell you.

2033
01:25:43,930 --> 01:25:46,350
Well, I'm afraid
you'll have to stay, then.

2034
01:25:48,977 --> 01:25:51,021
I wonder
if she's acting.

2035
01:25:51,104 --> 01:25:52,856
Hmm?

2036
01:25:55,984 --> 01:25:57,194
Where'd you get this?

2037
01:25:57,277 --> 01:25:59,363
That? I bought that
at an auction.

2038
01:25:59,446 --> 01:26:02,032
It's just an antique.
You can't fire it.

2039
01:26:03,325 --> 01:26:04,493
[gunshot]

2040
01:26:05,744 --> 01:26:07,454
Just an antique, huh?

2041
01:26:07,537 --> 01:26:09,581
Here's another one.

2042
01:26:14,336 --> 01:26:17,339
Well, quite an arsenal
for a peaceful community.

2043
01:26:17,422 --> 01:26:18,757
MacGregor: Well,
what's your story?

2044
01:26:18,840 --> 01:26:21,218
Tatum: Why... I need it,
working around the bank.

2045
01:26:21,301 --> 01:26:23,303
Well, we're not around
the bank now, Mr. Tatum.

2046
01:26:23,387 --> 01:26:24,429
So i'm sure you can

2047
01:26:24,513 --> 01:26:25,889
spare it
for a few minutes.

2048
01:26:25,972 --> 01:26:27,265
Charles, if you can't
vindicate these actions,

2049
01:26:27,349 --> 01:26:29,059
I'll see that you
go to jail.

2050
01:26:29,142 --> 01:26:31,019
I'll keep that
in mind, Mr. Ronson.

2051
01:26:31,103 --> 01:26:33,355
Now, dad, I'm going to use
your fluoroscope for a moment.

2052
01:26:33,438 --> 01:26:34,815
Alright.

2053
01:26:34,898 --> 01:26:36,483
Slugs, will you close
those curtains, please?

2054
01:26:36,566 --> 01:26:38,902
And, Mickey,
you might keep an eye

2055
01:26:38,985 --> 01:26:40,529
on the Draque family.

2056
01:26:40,612 --> 01:26:42,572
Now, if you'll all gather around
the fluoroscope here,

2057
01:26:42,656 --> 01:26:44,491
I'll proceed
to the demonstration.

2058
01:26:44,574 --> 01:26:46,868
Mr. Ronson, just move
in here close, will you?

2059
01:26:46,952 --> 01:26:51,248
Yes, and you, too, Willoughby.
And Bill Burns.

2060
01:26:51,331 --> 01:26:54,793
Alright, now if someone
will just close those curtains.

2061
01:26:55,877 --> 01:26:58,839
Nick: All set?

2062
01:26:58,922 --> 01:27:01,007
- Anybody know what that is?
- Golly!

2063
01:27:01,091 --> 01:27:03,343
Nora: I got a bargain...
two pictures.

2064
01:27:03,427 --> 01:27:04,720
Nick: And i don't mean
the windmill

2065
01:27:04,803 --> 01:27:07,264
or this little dog
down here in the corner.

2066
01:27:08,056 --> 01:27:09,641
Look closely.

2067
01:27:09,725 --> 01:27:12,060
Willoughby, don't you
recognize that?

2068
01:27:12,144 --> 01:27:13,228
Good heavens.

2069
01:27:13,311 --> 01:27:14,771
Holy smokes.

2070
01:27:14,855 --> 01:27:17,107
Alright,
open the curtains.

2071
01:27:18,775 --> 01:27:20,318
Well, Willoughby...

2072
01:27:22,821 --> 01:27:24,990
Why, it's part of the plans
for the propeller.

2073
01:27:25,073 --> 01:27:27,200
That's right.
A foreign power

2074
01:27:27,284 --> 01:27:28,827
would pay a lot
of money for that.

2075
01:27:28,910 --> 01:27:30,287
They couldn't be stolen.

2076
01:27:30,370 --> 01:27:31,788
Why not? This was.

2077
01:27:31,872 --> 01:27:33,832
We've protected
ourselves against it.

2078
01:27:33,915 --> 01:27:36,710
The plans are divided
into five different parts.

2079
01:27:36,793 --> 01:27:38,920
Nobody is allowed
to see or to work

2080
01:27:39,004 --> 01:27:40,422
on more than one part.

2081
01:27:40,505 --> 01:27:42,132
Is that so?

2082
01:27:42,215 --> 01:27:44,551
Oh, slugs, let's have
those other four paintings.

2083
01:27:44,634 --> 01:27:46,136
Here they are, Nick.

2084
01:27:46,219 --> 01:27:48,805
And, uh, tell them
where you got them.

2085
01:27:48,889 --> 01:27:50,223
Why, where
you told me...

2086
01:27:50,307 --> 01:27:52,642
in Anthony Croner's
art gallery in New York.

2087
01:27:52,726 --> 01:27:55,854
Anthony Croner, known
to his intimates as Tony.

2088
01:27:55,937 --> 01:27:57,147
Make a note
of that, Mr. Draque.

2089
01:27:57,230 --> 01:28:01,109
<i>Oh, Mr. Crump,
you recognize these?</i>

2090
01:28:01,193 --> 01:28:02,819
Oh, gracious me.

2091
01:28:02,903 --> 01:28:04,196
Yes. Well, those
are the pictures

2092
01:28:04,279 --> 01:28:06,448
I sold to her.

2093
01:28:06,531 --> 01:28:09,117
Thank you.

2094
01:28:09,201 --> 01:28:11,536
Under these four
innocent-looking paintings

2095
01:28:11,620 --> 01:28:12,913
are the designs

2096
01:28:12,996 --> 01:28:14,206
for the other parts
of your propeller.

2097
01:28:14,289 --> 01:28:15,373
Surprised?

2098
01:28:15,457 --> 01:28:17,667
Yes, I am.

2099
01:28:17,751 --> 01:28:20,045
Bill, will you
tell me now

2100
01:28:20,128 --> 01:28:21,797
why you fought
with Peter Berton?

2101
01:28:21,880 --> 01:28:23,882
Well, he tried to
push me out of my job,

2102
01:28:23,965 --> 01:28:25,467
always making trouble.

2103
01:28:25,550 --> 01:28:26,718
What kind of trouble?

2104
01:28:26,802 --> 01:28:28,678
Angling for
somebody else's job.

2105
01:28:28,762 --> 01:28:30,472
He was always
doing that.

2106
01:28:30,555 --> 01:28:32,224
He should have
been fired.

2107
01:28:32,307 --> 01:28:33,433
Why wasn't he?

2108
01:28:33,517 --> 01:28:34,768
That's what
i'd like to know.

2109
01:28:34,851 --> 01:28:37,103
He must have had
a drag somewhere.

2110
01:28:37,187 --> 01:28:38,396
Willoughby
would just switch him

2111
01:28:38,480 --> 01:28:40,106
from one
department to another.

2112
01:28:40,190 --> 01:28:41,817
Nick: Hmm...

2113
01:28:41,900 --> 01:28:45,195
See what i mean?
The finger's on him now.

2114
01:28:45,278 --> 01:28:46,738
But my money's
on Brogan.

2115
01:28:46,822 --> 01:28:47,989
[door opens]

2116
01:28:48,073 --> 01:28:49,407
Thank you.

2117
01:28:49,491 --> 01:28:50,826
Oh, I'm sorry
to be late, Nick.

2118
01:28:50,909 --> 01:28:52,077
I was up
at Mrs. Stanton's.

2119
01:28:52,160 --> 01:28:53,286
You know, that
baby's about due.

2120
01:28:53,370 --> 01:28:54,621
Oh. Well, I'm glad
you came, Bruce.

2121
01:28:54,704 --> 01:28:55,997
I'm going to need you.

2122
01:28:56,081 --> 01:28:57,499
Shall we search him
for weapons, too?

2123
01:28:57,582 --> 01:28:59,835
Sure. Everybody's
doing it.

2124
01:28:59,918 --> 01:29:01,044
Well, I surrender.

2125
01:29:01,127 --> 01:29:03,004
- Uh-oh.
- Here's something.

2126
01:29:04,923 --> 01:29:05,966
Is that loaded?

2127
01:29:06,049 --> 01:29:07,384
Just with blanks.

2128
01:29:07,467 --> 01:29:08,802
Bruce, we're trying
to get all the facts

2129
01:29:08,885 --> 01:29:10,387
about Peter Berton...

2130
01:29:10,470 --> 01:29:12,681
how he lived
and how he died.

2131
01:29:14,057 --> 01:29:15,976
By the way,
when i phoned you

2132
01:29:16,059 --> 01:29:17,227
right after
Berton was shot,

2133
01:29:17,310 --> 01:29:18,603
where were you
in your house?

2134
01:29:18,687 --> 01:29:20,605
Well, let's see.
Oh, sure, I remember.

2135
01:29:20,689 --> 01:29:22,482
I was working
on my stamp collection

2136
01:29:22,566 --> 01:29:24,150
all that evening
in my study.

2137
01:29:24,234 --> 01:29:26,570
Hmm. No one disturbed you
during the evening?

2138
01:29:26,653 --> 01:29:28,280
No. Well, I had
one patient.

2139
01:29:28,363 --> 01:29:29,990
Ah. But you didn't
hear the shot?

2140
01:29:30,073 --> 01:29:32,534
- No, I didn't.
- No.

2141
01:29:32,617 --> 01:29:34,202
Alright, Willoughby,
maybe you'd like

2142
01:29:34,286 --> 01:29:36,788
to explain to us now
about Berton.

2143
01:29:36,872 --> 01:29:39,583
Well, the boy just didn't seem
to get along with people.

2144
01:29:39,666 --> 01:29:41,334
You could have discharged him,
couldn't you?

2145
01:29:41,418 --> 01:29:44,004
Yes. But he seemed
such a nice, honest chap.

2146
01:29:44,087 --> 01:29:45,255
Ah.

2147
01:29:45,338 --> 01:29:47,757
Well, he was
a very good workman.

2148
01:29:47,841 --> 01:29:49,384
Why don't you tell
the truth, Willoughby?

2149
01:29:49,467 --> 01:29:50,552
You were told
to take care of him.

2150
01:29:50,635 --> 01:29:51,720
You had orders.

2151
01:29:51,803 --> 01:29:52,846
Orders from whom?

2152
01:29:52,929 --> 01:29:54,180
From someone higher up,

2153
01:29:54,264 --> 01:29:55,974
someone on the board
of directors...

2154
01:29:56,057 --> 01:29:57,475
Mr. Ronson.

2155
01:29:58,727 --> 01:29:59,853
I gave no orders.

2156
01:29:59,936 --> 01:30:01,521
The boy was
recommended to me,

2157
01:30:01,605 --> 01:30:03,148
and i asked Willoughby
to look after him. That's all.

2158
01:30:03,231 --> 01:30:04,774
Come on, Willoughby.
You better speak up.

2159
01:30:04,858 --> 01:30:06,526
I refuse to be held
responsible for this.

2160
01:30:06,610 --> 01:30:09,029
I wanted to let him go.
Mr. Ronson wouldn't let me.

2161
01:30:09,112 --> 01:30:10,155
That's a lie!

2162
01:30:10,238 --> 01:30:11,823
Oh, is it,
Mr. Ronson?

2163
01:30:11,907 --> 01:30:13,825
<i>I think we both know
better than that.</i>

2164
01:30:13,909 --> 01:30:15,452
Bruce, what time was it

2165
01:30:15,535 --> 01:30:16,912
when we got out
to Crazy Mary's last night?

2166
01:30:16,995 --> 01:30:18,079
- You mean, the last time?
- Yes.

2167
01:30:18,163 --> 01:30:19,497
About midnight.

2168
01:30:19,581 --> 01:30:20,540
And about how long would
you say she'd been dead?

2169
01:30:20,624 --> 01:30:21,791
About half an hour.

2170
01:30:21,875 --> 01:30:23,335
Certainly not more
than an hour.

2171
01:30:23,418 --> 01:30:24,628
Ah. How does that
check with you, Mr. Ronson?

2172
01:30:24,711 --> 01:30:26,296
With me?
What do i know about it?

2173
01:30:26,379 --> 01:30:27,756
You ought to know. You were
in her shack last night.

2174
01:30:27,839 --> 01:30:29,424
I...in her shack?

2175
01:30:29,507 --> 01:30:32,677
Certainly, after you
bopped Mrs. Draque on the head.

2176
01:30:32,761 --> 01:30:34,471
Sit down,
goldilocks.

2177
01:30:34,554 --> 01:30:36,181
You bopped her on the head,
grabbed this painting,

2178
01:30:36,264 --> 01:30:37,515
and took it
out to Crazy Mary's.

2179
01:30:37,599 --> 01:30:38,767
I never heard
anything so absurd.

2180
01:30:38,850 --> 01:30:40,393
Look here, Nick.

2181
01:30:40,477 --> 01:30:43,355
You're making some rather
serious accusations.

2182
01:30:43,438 --> 01:30:45,690
Sam Ronson wouldn't do
a thing like that.

2183
01:30:47,734 --> 01:30:49,819
Dad, I know this is going
to sound a little fantastic,

2184
01:30:49,903 --> 01:30:53,782
but i'm going to tell you
a little fairy tale.

2185
01:30:53,865 --> 01:30:55,659
Once upon a time
in this town,

2186
01:30:55,742 --> 01:30:58,411
oh, about 20-odd
years ago,

2187
01:30:58,495 --> 01:31:00,246
a local playboy
ran off to Boston

2188
01:31:00,330 --> 01:31:02,874
with a young housemaid
to get married.

2189
01:31:02,958 --> 01:31:04,292
Unfortunately,
the housemaid

2190
01:31:04,376 --> 01:31:07,295
wasn't quite right
in the head.

2191
01:31:07,379 --> 01:31:09,255
Well, in Boston,
the playboy

2192
01:31:09,339 --> 01:31:11,758
got into a barroom brawl
and was Killed,

2193
01:31:11,841 --> 01:31:14,678
leaving the housemaid
in a very tough spot.

2194
01:31:14,761 --> 01:31:17,847
Seems a baby
was on the way.

2195
01:31:17,931 --> 01:31:20,517
Now, the dead playboy
had a big brother,

2196
01:31:20,600 --> 01:31:23,103
but brother wanted
no part of it.

2197
01:31:23,186 --> 01:31:24,688
So, the housemaid
had to go

2198
01:31:24,771 --> 01:31:26,439
to a county hospital in Boston
to have her baby,

2199
01:31:26,523 --> 01:31:28,984
and the records
show that later,

2200
01:31:29,067 --> 01:31:31,778
she placed him in
a children's home there

2201
01:31:31,861 --> 01:31:34,698
under the name
of Peter Berton.

2202
01:31:37,617 --> 01:31:39,577
Shall i go on,
Mr. Ronson?

2203
01:31:42,956 --> 01:31:46,668
No. No, you win, Nick.

2204
01:31:46,751 --> 01:31:49,295
Perhaps you'd rather
tell us about it yourself.

2205
01:31:49,379 --> 01:31:50,714
I tried to help her,

2206
01:31:50,797 --> 01:31:54,217
but she was so...
so irrational.

2207
01:31:54,300 --> 01:31:56,261
The boy grew up
in the orphanage.

2208
01:31:56,344 --> 01:31:57,595
When he was of age,
I sent for him

2209
01:31:57,679 --> 01:31:59,806
and got him a job
here in the plant.

2210
01:31:59,889 --> 01:32:02,851
He didn't seem quite
well-balanced to me,

2211
01:32:02,934 --> 01:32:05,061
but Crazy Mary
kept hounding me.

2212
01:32:05,145 --> 01:32:07,772
I didn't want any scandal,
for my daughter's sake.

2213
01:32:10,608 --> 01:32:12,152
Well, everything
went on alright

2214
01:32:12,235 --> 01:32:14,279
until Crazy Mary
discovered that her boy

2215
01:32:14,362 --> 01:32:15,822
was mixed up in a racket

2216
01:32:15,905 --> 01:32:19,743
to copy some
propeller designs.

2217
01:32:19,826 --> 01:32:23,413
She wanted to stop him,
but she was helpless

2218
01:32:23,496 --> 01:32:26,166
without revealing to him
that she was his mother.

2219
01:32:26,249 --> 01:32:30,086
However, when the boy
up and got himself killed,

2220
01:32:30,170 --> 01:32:32,005
there was something
she could do.

2221
01:32:32,088 --> 01:32:34,340
She could protect
his good name.

2222
01:32:34,424 --> 01:32:36,259
So, she blackmailed
Mr. Ronson

2223
01:32:36,342 --> 01:32:38,053
into removing the evidence
against her boy...

2224
01:32:38,136 --> 01:32:39,596
this painting.

2225
01:32:39,679 --> 01:32:41,014
He took it to her
last night

2226
01:32:41,097 --> 01:32:44,142
after he removed it
from Mrs. Draque's room.

2227
01:32:44,225 --> 01:32:45,560
Is that true, Mr. Ronson?

2228
01:32:45,643 --> 01:32:48,271
Yes, but i didn't
kill Crazy Mary.

2229
01:32:48,354 --> 01:32:49,814
No, but you slugged me!

2230
01:32:49,898 --> 01:32:51,941
Why, you
small-town thug!

2231
01:32:52,025 --> 01:32:53,568
Ah!

2232
01:32:53,651 --> 01:32:55,278
Now, now, Mrs. Draque.

2233
01:32:55,361 --> 01:32:56,654
Just keep on doing
what you've been doing.

2234
01:32:56,738 --> 01:32:59,282
I'll have the cocoa
in a few minutes.

2235
01:32:59,365 --> 01:33:01,493
Well, now we know
the technique

2236
01:33:01,576 --> 01:33:03,828
that was used to deliver
these paintings.

2237
01:33:03,912 --> 01:33:05,747
Berton copied the plans,
painted over them,

2238
01:33:05,830 --> 01:33:09,709
and placed the paintings
for sale with Willy Crump.

2239
01:33:09,793 --> 01:33:12,462
Mrs. Draque bought them,
and through her husband,

2240
01:33:12,545 --> 01:33:15,215
they were delivered
at Tony Croner's in New York...

2241
01:33:15,298 --> 01:33:17,467
a nice, safe
arrangement,

2242
01:33:17,550 --> 01:33:20,762
very little danger
and lots of money

2243
01:33:20,845 --> 01:33:22,097
in it for everybody,
thousands.

2244
01:33:22,180 --> 01:33:23,723
What?

2245
01:33:23,807 --> 01:33:25,391
Does that surprise
you, Mrs. Draque?

2246
01:33:25,475 --> 01:33:27,602
Tell him
nothing, honey.

2247
01:33:27,685 --> 01:33:28,937
You mean you haven't
told your honey

2248
01:33:29,020 --> 01:33:30,605
just how many thousands
Croner gave you

2249
01:33:30,688 --> 01:33:31,898
every time you delivered

2250
01:33:31,981 --> 01:33:32,941
one of these paintings
to his gallery?

2251
01:33:33,024 --> 01:33:34,067
That's a lie.

2252
01:33:34,150 --> 01:33:35,527
Well, I just
don't think

2253
01:33:35,610 --> 01:33:36,861
you should have been
cheated, Mrs. Draque.

2254
01:33:36,945 --> 01:33:38,905
After all,
you took a big risk,

2255
01:33:38,988 --> 01:33:41,491
and now you're
involved in a murder.

2256
01:33:41,574 --> 01:33:44,953
Oh, no. I didn't have anything
to do with that.

2257
01:33:45,036 --> 01:33:47,122
I only bought the paintings
and turned them over to Edgar...

2258
01:33:47,205 --> 01:33:49,624
Shut up. You're blabbing
just like he wants you to.

2259
01:33:49,707 --> 01:33:51,751
I don't care! i'm not getting
mixed up in any murder!

2260
01:33:51,835 --> 01:33:53,962
You didn't
tell me it was...

2261
01:33:54,045 --> 01:33:57,298
Someone's always hitting
that poor Mrs. Draque.

2262
01:33:57,382 --> 01:34:00,927
Draque, you arranged
the scheme to steal these plans

2263
01:34:01,010 --> 01:34:03,555
through someone here
in Sycamore Springs,

2264
01:34:03,638 --> 01:34:04,931
someone who lives here

2265
01:34:05,014 --> 01:34:07,600
and is well regarded
in the community.

2266
01:34:07,684 --> 01:34:08,977
When we find who that
individual was...

2267
01:34:09,060 --> 01:34:11,187
Nick, look out!

2268
01:34:11,271 --> 01:34:12,814
Hilda: [screaming]
Gracious me!

2269
01:34:12,897 --> 01:34:14,065
[barking]

2270
01:34:16,484 --> 01:34:17,902
Here you are, Nick.

2271
01:34:17,986 --> 01:34:19,154
It was exactly
where you said.

2272
01:34:19,237 --> 01:34:20,321
There's one
cartridge missing.

2273
01:34:20,405 --> 01:34:22,866
Ah, yeah.

2274
01:34:22,949 --> 01:34:24,909
Ladies and gentlemen,

2275
01:34:24,993 --> 01:34:27,287
this is a rifle
called an Ambu.

2276
01:34:27,370 --> 01:34:31,583
It's used by Japanese snipers
in the Southwest Pacific.

2277
01:34:31,666 --> 01:34:34,752
It has long range
and great accuracy.

2278
01:34:34,836 --> 01:34:36,546
And this one's equipped
with a silencer.

2279
01:34:36,629 --> 01:34:37,672
Many of them
were brought back

2280
01:34:37,755 --> 01:34:39,090
by our boys
as souvenirs.

2281
01:34:39,174 --> 01:34:40,633
My brother Tom
brought that gun back.

2282
01:34:40,717 --> 01:34:42,010
Yes, that's right.

2283
01:34:42,093 --> 01:34:43,136
You're not trying
to imply that he...

2284
01:34:43,219 --> 01:34:44,345
I'm not implying anything.

2285
01:34:44,429 --> 01:34:45,638
I just agree that
it was his gun.

2286
01:34:45,722 --> 01:34:47,515
I think that's as good
as implying it.

2287
01:34:47,599 --> 01:34:49,392
Bertram: I agree
with Bruce, Nick.

2288
01:34:49,475 --> 01:34:51,269
These people
are my friends.

2289
01:34:51,352 --> 01:34:52,896
A little while ago,
you had us believing

2290
01:34:52,979 --> 01:34:54,522
Sam Ronson was guilty.

2291
01:34:54,606 --> 01:34:55,815
Ronson's just
a red herring.

2292
01:34:55,899 --> 01:34:57,650
I don't care if
he is a red herring.

2293
01:34:57,734 --> 01:34:59,944
I'll never believe
Sam Ronson killed anybody.

2294
01:35:00,028 --> 01:35:02,155
He didn't kill
Crazy Mary, dad.

2295
01:35:02,238 --> 01:35:03,948
When he arrived at her shack,
she was already dead.

2296
01:35:04,032 --> 01:35:05,241
How do you know that?

2297
01:35:05,325 --> 01:35:06,576
Well, he took
the painting to her.

2298
01:35:06,659 --> 01:35:07,827
That was the evidence
she wanted.

2299
01:35:07,911 --> 01:35:09,245
Had she been alive,

2300
01:35:09,329 --> 01:35:11,206
she would have
destroyed it immediately.

2301
01:35:11,289 --> 01:35:12,290
Apparently, she never
got her hands on it.

2302
01:35:12,373 --> 01:35:13,499
Man: Let go of me.

2303
01:35:13,583 --> 01:35:14,626
You got no right
to bring me here!

2304
01:35:14,709 --> 01:35:16,211
I haven't done anything!

2305
01:35:16,294 --> 01:35:19,047
Tom, I tried to get away.
They wouldn't let me.

2306
01:35:20,924 --> 01:35:22,383
What's the big idea?

2307
01:35:22,467 --> 01:35:24,427
Come in, Tom,
and join the party.

2308
01:35:24,510 --> 01:35:26,721
We're trying to
catch a murderer.

2309
01:35:26,804 --> 01:35:30,141
Bruce, according to
your autopsy report,

2310
01:35:30,225 --> 01:35:33,061
Peter Berton was shot
with a .45 revolver,

2311
01:35:33,144 --> 01:35:35,563
the bullet entering
the large left rhomboid,

2312
01:35:35,647 --> 01:35:37,815
puncturing the posterior lobe
of the left lung

2313
01:35:37,899 --> 01:35:38,858
and the lower lobe
of the right lung,

2314
01:35:38,942 --> 01:35:40,109
lacerating the parenchyma,

2315
01:35:40,193 --> 01:35:41,653
grazing the aorta,

2316
01:35:41,736 --> 01:35:43,613
and lodging against
the 12th right costal rib.

2317
01:35:43,696 --> 01:35:44,739
That's your boy.

2318
01:35:44,822 --> 01:35:46,407
Nick: In other words,

2319
01:35:46,491 --> 01:35:47,742
it entered about here,

2320
01:35:47,825 --> 01:35:49,410
passed all the way
through his body,

2321
01:35:49,494 --> 01:35:50,495
and ended up down there.

2322
01:35:50,578 --> 01:35:52,247
- Is that right?
- That's right.

2323
01:35:52,330 --> 01:35:53,706
Well, that's
very strange,

2324
01:35:53,790 --> 01:35:55,416
because
for a .45 revolver

2325
01:35:55,500 --> 01:35:57,252
to get that amount
of penetration,

2326
01:35:57,335 --> 01:35:59,754
it would have to be fired
almost point-blank.

2327
01:35:59,837 --> 01:36:01,297
And for a bullet
to have traveled

2328
01:36:01,381 --> 01:36:03,049
downward at such an angle,

2329
01:36:03,132 --> 01:36:04,634
the revolver would have
to have been fired

2330
01:36:04,717 --> 01:36:08,179
from some little gremlin
hanging from our porch roof.

2331
01:36:08,263 --> 01:36:09,931
Well, there was
no little gremlin.

2332
01:36:10,014 --> 01:36:11,808
So he couldn't have been
shot with a revolver.

2333
01:36:11,891 --> 01:36:14,477
No. The bullet
that killed Peter Berton

2334
01:36:14,560 --> 01:36:16,688
was fired from a rifle

2335
01:36:16,771 --> 01:36:19,857
from a distance
and at an elevation,

2336
01:36:19,941 --> 01:36:21,776
a rifle equipped
with a silencer,

2337
01:36:21,859 --> 01:36:23,361
a rifle like yours, Tom,

2338
01:36:23,444 --> 01:36:25,071
which, by the way,
has one bullet missing.

2339
01:36:25,154 --> 01:36:26,364
What are you
driving at, Nick?

2340
01:36:26,447 --> 01:36:28,324
Simply this...
Bruce, you switched

2341
01:36:28,408 --> 01:36:30,034
bullets on us
at the autopsy.

2342
01:36:30,118 --> 01:36:31,577
It was a Japanese
rifle bullet

2343
01:36:31,661 --> 01:36:33,413
you removed
from Berton's body,

2344
01:36:33,496 --> 01:36:34,998
but it was a .45
revolver bullet

2345
01:36:35,081 --> 01:36:36,291
that you handed
MacGregor.

2346
01:36:36,374 --> 01:36:39,252
What's the answer?

2347
01:36:39,335 --> 01:36:41,212
Well, I did that
to protect Tom,

2348
01:36:41,296 --> 01:36:43,089
because everybody knew
how jealous he was of Berton

2349
01:36:43,172 --> 01:36:44,882
on account of Laurabel.

2350
01:36:44,966 --> 01:36:46,634
You thought Tom might
have killed Berton?

2351
01:36:46,718 --> 01:36:49,429
No, but what
was i to think?

2352
01:36:49,512 --> 01:36:51,639
He had been raving
around the house that night.

2353
01:36:51,723 --> 01:36:52,724
Oh, indeed?

2354
01:36:52,807 --> 01:36:54,309
[door opens]

2355
01:36:54,392 --> 01:36:56,185
Oh, uh, Mrs. Hobbi,
on the night of the murder,

2356
01:36:56,269 --> 01:36:57,979
when i phoned
Dr. Clayworth to come over,

2357
01:36:58,062 --> 01:36:59,397
where was he?

2358
01:36:59,480 --> 01:37:01,357
He was upstairs, sir.

2359
01:37:01,441 --> 01:37:03,526
You're quite sure
of that?

2360
01:37:03,609 --> 01:37:05,028
Yes, sir.

2361
01:37:05,111 --> 01:37:06,571
I remember distinctly

2362
01:37:06,654 --> 01:37:08,072
of going to the stairs
to call him.

2363
01:37:08,156 --> 01:37:09,490
Uh-huh. And how long
before that

2364
01:37:09,574 --> 01:37:11,242
had Mr. Berton
left the house?

2365
01:37:11,326 --> 01:37:12,869
Well, just
a few minutes, sir.

2366
01:37:12,952 --> 01:37:15,121
That's all.
Thank you.

2367
01:37:15,204 --> 01:37:16,622
So, I was right,
Bruce.

2368
01:37:16,706 --> 01:37:17,957
Berton was
at your house.

2369
01:37:18,041 --> 01:37:19,375
Well, I told you
i had a patient, Nick.

2370
01:37:19,459 --> 01:37:20,585
Yes, but you
withheld the fact

2371
01:37:20,668 --> 01:37:22,503
that the patient
was Peter Berton.

2372
01:37:22,587 --> 01:37:24,047
It seems you
were not downstairs

2373
01:37:24,130 --> 01:37:25,715
in your study all evening,
as you said.

2374
01:37:25,798 --> 01:37:27,884
I might have,
for a minute...

2375
01:37:27,967 --> 01:37:30,178
Are you trying to
blame this on me?

2376
01:37:30,261 --> 01:37:33,139
Bruce, when we
went out to visit

2377
01:37:33,222 --> 01:37:35,099
Crazy Mary the first time,
you stood outside

2378
01:37:35,183 --> 01:37:36,267
and called to her.
Remember?

2379
01:37:36,351 --> 01:37:37,810
What's the matter
with that?

2380
01:37:37,894 --> 01:37:38,853
That's the only way
you can get in to see her.

2381
01:37:38,936 --> 01:37:39,896
Exactly,
but last night,

2382
01:37:39,979 --> 01:37:41,314
you didn't
bother to call.

2383
01:37:41,397 --> 01:37:43,232
You just barged right in.
Why was that?

2384
01:37:43,316 --> 01:37:45,818
I didn't just
barge in. I...

2385
01:37:45,902 --> 01:37:47,236
Well, I was excited,
I guess.

2386
01:37:47,320 --> 01:37:48,780
I don't know
why I didn't.

2387
01:37:48,863 --> 01:37:50,073
I'll tell you why.

2388
01:37:50,156 --> 01:37:51,115
Because it would have
been silly

2389
01:37:51,199 --> 01:37:52,825
to call to a dead woman,

2390
01:37:52,909 --> 01:37:55,078
and you knew she was dead
because you'd killed her.

2391
01:37:55,161 --> 01:37:56,579
I think you're crazy.

2392
01:37:56,662 --> 01:37:57,997
What was your business
with Draque?

2393
01:37:58,081 --> 01:37:59,499
I've never had
any business with Draque.

2394
01:37:59,582 --> 01:38:01,334
You called on him
frequently at his hotel.

2395
01:38:01,417 --> 01:38:02,627
I checked on that.

2396
01:38:02,710 --> 01:38:04,504
Oh, well,
that is professional.

2397
01:38:04,587 --> 01:38:06,839
He was a patient
of mine.

2398
01:38:06,923 --> 01:38:10,176
A patient?
Is that right, Draque?

2399
01:38:10,259 --> 01:38:11,928
That's right.

2400
01:38:12,011 --> 01:38:13,346
It's true?

2401
01:38:15,556 --> 01:38:17,934
He's never been sick
a day since i've known him.

2402
01:38:18,017 --> 01:38:19,185
Thank you.

2403
01:38:19,268 --> 01:38:21,562
Uh-uh.

2404
01:38:21,646 --> 01:38:23,022
The truth is that
Draque gave you a chance

2405
01:38:23,106 --> 01:38:24,565
to pick up
some important money,

2406
01:38:24,649 --> 01:38:26,442
and you talked that
bumble-brained Berton kid

2407
01:38:26,526 --> 01:38:28,152
into carrying out
the scheme.

2408
01:38:28,236 --> 01:38:29,278
When the news got out
that i was here

2409
01:38:29,362 --> 01:38:31,322
on a mysterious
investigation,

2410
01:38:31,406 --> 01:38:32,824
Berton got into
a panic and decided

2411
01:38:32,907 --> 01:38:34,659
to come to me and make
a clean breast of it.

2412
01:38:34,742 --> 01:38:36,244
That would have
cooked your goose.

2413
01:38:36,327 --> 01:38:38,538
So, when Berton left your house
and came over here,

2414
01:38:38,621 --> 01:38:39,956
you rushed up to
your brother's room,

2415
01:38:40,039 --> 01:38:41,499
grabbed his rifle,

2416
01:38:41,582 --> 01:38:43,292
and just as Berton reached
our door, you shot him.

2417
01:38:43,376 --> 01:38:44,335
You're a liar.

2418
01:38:44,419 --> 01:38:46,295
No, you're
the liar, Bruce.

2419
01:38:46,379 --> 01:38:48,423
You lied about
your association with Draque.

2420
01:38:48,506 --> 01:38:50,716
You lied about being downstairs
when Berton was shot.

2421
01:38:50,800 --> 01:38:52,593
You knew Crazy Mary was dead
when we went there.

2422
01:38:52,677 --> 01:38:54,387
You switched bullets
at Berton's autopsy.

2423
01:38:54,470 --> 01:38:57,056
I told you i did that
to protect Tom!

2424
01:38:57,140 --> 01:38:59,350
Miss Ronson, where was Tom

2425
01:38:59,434 --> 01:39:01,727
the night that Peter
was murdered?

2426
01:39:01,811 --> 01:39:04,355
He was in Boston.
I phoned him that night.

2427
01:39:04,439 --> 01:39:06,190
Nick: So, you weren't
protecting Tom.

2428
01:39:06,274 --> 01:39:09,986
You were protecting yourself.
Any other answers, Bruce?

2429
01:39:10,069 --> 01:39:14,449
Yeah. I...
I've got one more.

2430
01:39:14,532 --> 01:39:17,118
Oh, you were always
the smart boy, Nick.

2431
01:39:17,201 --> 01:39:18,619
You knew
all the answers.

2432
01:39:18,703 --> 01:39:19,745
You caught
the big fish.

2433
01:39:19,829 --> 01:39:21,164
You beat me
at everything.

2434
01:39:21,247 --> 01:39:22,290
Now it's going to be
different this time.

2435
01:39:22,373 --> 01:39:23,541
It's going to be a tie.

2436
01:39:23,624 --> 01:39:25,585
You've got me,
but i've got you.

2437
01:39:25,668 --> 01:39:26,961
You haven't the nerve
to pull the trigger.

2438
01:39:27,044 --> 01:39:28,129
Oh, haven't i,
though?

2439
01:39:28,212 --> 01:39:29,172
No!

2440
01:39:29,255 --> 01:39:31,090
[click]

2441
01:39:31,174 --> 01:39:33,092
- Drop it, Bruce.
- Leave me alone!

2442
01:39:33,176 --> 01:39:34,594
Take your hands
off me!

2443
01:39:34,677 --> 01:39:36,137
I forgot
to tell you.

2444
01:39:36,220 --> 01:39:38,806
Brogan removed the firing pin
from that gun.

2445
01:39:38,890 --> 01:39:41,225
MacGregor: Get him out, men.
- He can't beat me again!

2446
01:39:41,309 --> 01:39:42,268
Let me at him!

2447
01:39:42,351 --> 01:39:44,937
You can't beat me again!

2448
01:39:45,021 --> 01:39:48,357
Mr. Charles, I've been
wanting to do this

2449
01:39:48,441 --> 01:39:50,485
ever since you got here.

2450
01:39:50,568 --> 01:39:52,069
May i have
your autograph?

2451
01:39:52,153 --> 01:39:55,490
It's for my mother
in Walla Walla.

2452
01:39:59,744 --> 01:40:02,663
Gee... Thanks.

2453
01:40:02,747 --> 01:40:04,707
That was
wonderful, Nick.

2454
01:40:04,790 --> 01:40:06,751
Great work, my boy.

2455
01:40:06,834 --> 01:40:09,003
[chuckles]

2456
01:40:09,086 --> 01:40:10,880
Well.

2457
01:40:13,049 --> 01:40:16,385
Nora: Why, Nicky, I do believe
you popped a button.

2458
01:40:17,428 --> 01:40:20,348
[instrumental music]

